(44,'Chungdong First Methodist Church','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Chungdong-First-Methodist-Church/ENP002132','Chungdong First Methodist Church is Korea??s first Protestant church, established in 1885 by American Methodist missionary Henry Appenzeller. The church is Korea\'s representative Protestant church. Chungdong First Methodist operates many religious and missionary programs such as medical services, education services, and missionary training for dispatch to foreign countries.','+82-2-753-0001~3','Worship Services in English:  \n- Contemporary Worship:  Sundays, 9:30 KST (Bethel Chapel)\n- Traditional Worship with Holy Communion:  Sundays, 14:00 KST  (Main Sanctuary)\n\nThe Mangon Christian History Reference Room requires advance reservation to visit. ','The Mangon Christian History Reference Room is closed Mondays and Sundays','04516  46 Jeongdong-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/2  City Hall Station  Exit 10,  404m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16427&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16428&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16429&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.565363,'ENP002132'),
(45,'Jinkwansa Temple','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Jinkwansa-Temple/ENP006251','Jinkwansa Temple is a centuries-old temple located in Bukhansan National Park. The temple was built by order of King Hyeonjong of the Goryeo Dynasty in gratitude to the great Buddhist priest Jinkwan. History has it that Jinkwan saved King Hyeon-jong\'s life when he was young and the king repaid the priest by building the temple. Jinkwansa Temple is comprised of several buildings and some of the notable buildings include Daeungjeon Hall, Myeongbujeon Hall, and Nahanjeon Hall. The temple also operates temple stay programs where visitors can experience Buddhist culture firsthand. There are programs for groups, children, and youths.','-8689','','','03308  73, Jingwan-gil, Eunpyeong-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gupabal Station  Exit 3, take bus 7211 or 7723 and get off at Hanago Station,  853m\nSubway Lines 3/6  Yeonsinnae Station  Exit 3, take bus 701 or 7211 and get off at Hanago Station, 853m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=30284&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=30285&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=30286&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=30287&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=30288&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.638141,'ENP006251'),
(46,'Hwanghakjeong (Archery Field)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Hwanghakjeong-Archery-Field/ENP029766','Hwanghakjeong is an archery field built by Emperor Gojong who strongly believed that archery was the best activity for training one\'s body and spirit. Originally located in Gyeonguigung Palace, this archery field was relocated here under Inwangsan Mountain during 1922. Known far and wide for its magnificent scenery, Hwanghakjeong is located next to Hwanghakjeong Korean Archery Gallery, allowing visitors to access all kinds of information about Korean archery in one place.','-6443','','','03027  15-32 Sajik-ro 9-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 1,  750m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22585&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22586&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',2.000000,37.577844,'ENP029766'),
(47,'Daegaksa Temple','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Daegaksa-Temple/ENP005015','Daegaksa Temple is a Buddhist temple founded in 1911 by Yongseong Seunim and located not far from Changdeokgung Palace. Yongseong Seunim was one of the 33 citizen representatives who took part in the March 1st Movement. He was active in the Korean independence movement and his legacy includes significant reforms of modern Buddhism in Korea. The temple was originally just a small hanok and in 1986 the temple was completely ry reconstructed. Today, Daegaksa has a main gate, belfry, and three-story temple.','-5166','Daily from sunrise to sunset.','Open year round','03134  87, Yulgok-ro 10-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/3/5  Jongno 3(sam)-ga Station  Exit 8,  139m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22637&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22638&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22639&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22640&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.573657,'ENP005015'),
(48,'Ehwajang (House)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Ehwajang-House/ENP002481','Ehwajang was the residence of Korea\'s first president Rhee Syngman. The residence now functions as a memorial hall for President Rhee Syngman. Ehwajang is comprised of the Rhee Syngman Memorial Hall, Sajeokgwan Library, and Jogakdang. Jogakdang was once the president??s office where Rhee designed and formed the first Korean presidential cabinet.','-1476','','','110-500  32, Ihwajang 1-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4, Hyehwa Station, Exit 2 (15 mins on foot)','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17290&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17291&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17292&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17293&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.578343,'ENP002481'),
(49,'Segeomjeong Pavilion','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Segeomjeong-Pavilion/ENP002395','Segeomjeong Pavilion is a well-known historic pavilion and was designated Monument of Seoul No. 4 in 1976. The pavilion itself and the surrounding area are both referred to as Segeomjeong. During the Coup of 1623, rebel forces passed through Changuimun Gate from Segeomjeong in order to attack the palace. In peaceful times during the Joseon Dynasty, guards and soldiers would rest here and clean their swords at the stream.','-1063','','','03018  244, Segeomjeong-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3, Hongje Station  Exits 1 / 2,  Take the 110A Korea University trunk bus from Yujin Shopping Center stop, get off at Segeomjeong/Sangmyung University stop, 85m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16511&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16512&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16513&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16514&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.600432,'ENP002395'),
(50,'Deoksugung Stonewall Walkway','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Deoksugung-Stone-Wall-Path/ENP023563','The Deoksugung Stone Wall Path is a charming walkway that winds around Deoksugung Palace in Jung-gu, Seoul, bordered by a rustic stone wall. Here, you can experience a serene blend of Joseon-era architecture and modern Seoul, with the path at its most beautiful in spring and autumn, attracting many visitors. After touring Deoksugung Palace, it??s an ideal spot to unwind at nearby cafes or galleries. The path also connects to Jeongdong-gil and the Seoul Museum of Art, making it easy to explore these attractions together.','-1405','Open year round \n*Interior walking path open Tuesday ??Sunday 9:00 ??21:00*','','04519  101 Sejong-daero, Jung-gu, Seoul, Deoksugung Stonewall Walkway (Underground)','Subway Lines 1 / 2, City Hall Station, Exit 1, 168m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68277&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68278&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68279&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68280&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72581&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.565607,'ENP023563'),
(51,'Gilsangsa Temple','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Gilsangsa-Temple/ENP003255','Gilsangsa Temple was once one of the foremost yojeong, a place where powerful men used to convene behind the scenes.The temple is named after the woman who donated the buildings, a gisaeng (a female entertainer and/or courtesan) named Kim Yeong-han who had a change of heart after reading \"Non-Possession\" by Venerable Beopjeong Sunim. The monk initially denied her request, but in 1995 decided to turn the buildings into a temple.  As a result, the temple has a very unusual atmosphere because it kept many of its original features. The temple is highly regarded for its involvement in cultural exchanges with other religions, and its programs to help visitors experience Buddhism.','-9537','Opening hours vary depending on the ceremony and temple schedule. Please refer to the website.','','68, Seonjam-ro 5-gil, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4, Hansung Univ. Station, Exit 6, 65m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65047&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65049&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65050&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65051&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65055&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.598702,'ENP003255'),
(52,'Seodaemun Independence Park','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seodaemun-Independence-Park/ENP001753','Seodaemun Independence Park is a park and important historic cultural site. During the Japanese colonial period, the park housed Seodaemun Prison. Japanese imperial authorities arrested and held political prisoners and independence activists here in brutal conditions before the liberation of Korea in 1945. Today, the park is home to a history museum and monuments to independence fighters.  At the Seodaemun Prison History Hall, visitors can learn about the history, struggles, and sacrifices made by Koreans during the colonial era. Visitors to the park can see the historic Dongnimmun Gate (Independence Gate), Independence Hall, and the March 1st Declaration of Independence Monument. There are several memorials and statues of patriots, such as a statue of Seo Jaepil (a Korean independence activist) and the Patriot Martyrs Monument.','-11365','Open 24 hours','','03732  251, Tongil-ro, Seodaemun-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Dongnimmun Station  Exits 4,  150m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67659&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67660&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67661&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67662&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67663&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.574486,'ENP001753'),
(53,'Amsa??dong Prehistoric Settlement Site','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Amsa%E2%80%93dong-Prehistoric-Settlement-Site/ENP002174','The Amsa-dong Prehistoric Settlement Site is a historic site where visitors can learn about Korea during the Neolithic era. The site has two exhibition halls with displays of ancient artifacts excavated at Amsa, and with educational displays about the lives of pre-historic people who lived during 5,000 BCE. Carbonized acorns, fishing net weights, and stone tools have been excavated at Amsa. Twenty five hut sites have been uncovered during excavations throughout the years and a total of nine huts have been restored to date.??,-9865,Daily 09:30 - 18:00,Closed Mondays & holidays ','','','','','','',0.000000,0.000000,'ENP002174'),
