(57,'Bongwonsa Temple','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Bongwonsa-Temple/ENP028339','Originally built on the site of Yonsei University by Queen Jinseong of the Shilla Dynasty in 889 A.D., Bongwonsa Temple was moved to its current site by King Yongjo of the Joseon Dynasty in 1748. The temple grounds holds a pond filled with lotus flowers. This attracts a lot of visitors, especially in the summer, as many gather to view the beautiful blooming flowers as they enjoy the festivities. It\'s the perfect place to visit for calming your mind and spirit.','-3319','','','03721  75-66, Bongwonsa-gil, Seodaemun-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 2, Sinchon Station, Exit 4\nSubway Line 2, Dongnimmun Station, Exit 4','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=21375&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=21376&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73597&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73598&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.571294,'ENP028339'),
(58,'Andong Presbyterian Church\'s Soheodang','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Andong-Presbyterian-Churchs-Soheodang/ENP002010','Andong Presbyterian Church is located in Bukchon Hanok Village. The church dates back to the early 20th century. Most churches at the time were founded and built by Western missionaries. However, Andong is unique in that the church was founded by Koreans. Soheodang is part of the church complex and it is a rest area run by the church. Visitors to Soheodang are welcome to sit and rest while enjoying free tea provided by the church.','-4048','* Operating hours vary according to the church\'s prayer service schedule. Please check the times on the church website before visiting.','','03061  57, Yunboseon-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 1,  305m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=1233&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=1234&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=1236&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.578404,'ENP002010'),
(59,'Chodae-gil Trail (Bugaksan Mountain)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Chodae-gil-Trail-Bukhansan-Mountain/ENP027112','Chodae-gil Trail is a walking trail course created near the base of Bukhansan Mountain to commemorate the opening of the Modern History Memorial Hall. On this course, visitors can visit the tombs of prominent figures who played key roles in the founding of Korea\'s modern history.    (Chodae-gil Trail Course) Modern History Memorial Hall ??Grave of Haegong Shin Ik-hee ??Grave of Martyr Ilsung Lee Jun ??Grave of Gain Kim Byeong-ro ??United Graves of the Independence Army ??Grave of Seongjae Lee Si-yeong - Total Distance: 1.3 km - Total Time: 30 mins','-6935','','','01013  114, 4.19-ro, Gangbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4, Suyu Station  Exit 4,  take Bus No. 01 (village) Gangbuk at Suyu Station Bus Stop ??Get off at Shinsung Villa Bus Stop, Modern and Contemporary History Museum','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20517&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20518&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20519&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.641067,'ENP027112'),
(60,'Cheongjeon Yi Sang-beom House','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-cjisbhouse/ENPlpqd8k','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}The house and studio of Cheongjeon Yi Sang-beom, an artist recognized for pioneering new directions in Korean Southern School painting, are located west of Gyeongbokgung in Nuha-dong. Built-in 1929, the Yi Sang-beom House is an urban hanok featuring an L-shaped main house and straight-line servant quarters. It is distinguished by its rare kitchen with a cool wooden floor. Yi lived in this small, renovated hanok in Nuha-dong for 43 years. In his studio, known as Cheongjeon Hwasuk, he produced many artworks and mentored exceptional students such as Bae Ryeom and Park No-soo.','','March-October 09:00-18:00\nNovember-February 09:30-17:00','Mondays','03039  31-7 Pirundae-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 2,  619m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65231&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65232&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65233&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65234&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65235&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.578391,'ENPlpqd8k'),
(61,'Jongmyo Shrine Stonewall Path','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-jongmyostonewall/ENP0wav1s','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}The Jongmyo Shrine Stonewall Path is a tranquil walkway that stretches along the western wall of Jongmyo Shrine, a UNESCO World Heritage site. Unlike well-known historical and cultural spots like Bukchon and Insadong, this pathway is a hidden gem that has recently gained popularity. Strolling along the pristine, elegant stone wall, visitors can leisurely explore nearby cafes, craft studios, and shops and cafes housed in renovated hanok buildings along the side alleys. The path is beautifully framed by the historic stone wall and lush trees, offering scenic views throughout the seasons. In spring, cherry blossoms and fresh leaves embrace the wall, creating a bright and cheerful atmosphere. In autumn, the wall is transformed into a picturesque setting draped in warm hues, perfect for a romantic walk. This peaceful spot offers an ideal escape from the busy pace of everyday life. Traditional architecture and nature are in harmonious balance, providing a calming ambiance. Jongmyo Stone Wall Path is a fantastic photo spot for capturing traces of Korea??s traditional culture. Walking along the path, visitors can conveniently explore nearby attractions, such as Changgyeonggung Palace, Changdeokgung Palace, Insadong, and Samcheong-dong, where tradition meets modernity, allowing for a well-rounded cultural experience.','','','','03135  104-1 Gwonnong-dong, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 5  Jongno 3-ga Station  Exit 7,  383m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68942&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68940&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68941&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68943&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68944&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.575540,'ENP0wav1s'),
(62,'Bonghwanggak Pavilion','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Bonghwanggak-Pavilion/ENP003305','Bonghwanggak Pavilion was constructed in 1912 by Son Byeonghui, the Korean independence activist. Bongwhanggak was built to be an educational facility that taught students the doctrines of Cheondogyo and educated leaders of the Korean independence movement. Cheondogyo is a Korean religion founded by Choe Je-U and its main tenet is that life and death are one, and all things in the universe repeat in an endless cycle. \"Bonghwang\" is the Korean word for the phoenix and it appeared often in Choe\'s writings, which is how the pavilion came to be named Bonghwanggak. The pavilion is considered the main shrine of Cheondogyo. In 1969, Bongwhanggak was designated Tangible Cultural Property No. 2 by the Seoul Metropolitan Government.','-40','','','142-090  107-12, Samyang-ro 173-gil, Gangbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Uisinseol Line Bukhansan Ui Station Exit 2, 659m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16415&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16416&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16417&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16418&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73599&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.660292,'ENP003305'),
(63,'Samcheongdong','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Samcheong-dong/ENP002121','Samcheongdong is Seoul\'s most stylish neighborhood, located just past Gyeongbokgung Palace\'s stone wall lined street. The name \"Samcheong\" is derived from the words \"sam\" meaning ??three\", and \"cheong\" meaning \"fresh\" or \"pure\", because the mountain, water and the heart of the people in this area are all very fresh and pure. Then it\'s not wonder why many artists have sought out Samcheong-dong over the years. Because of this, Samcheong-dong became known as an artistic area.      The area of Samcheongdong is actually made up of several neighborhoods: Anguk-dong, Sogyeok-dong, Hwa-dong, and Sagan-dong and ends at Samcheong Park. Samcheong-dong is dotted with various art museums, museums, art galleries, restaurants, cafés, and shops; some are traditional, some are modern, but all are unique and colorful.','-40','','','110-260  Gahoe-dong, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 2,  780m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73782&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73783&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=31361&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=24749&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=31366&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.582012,'ENP002121'),
(64,'Seoul Anglican Cathedral','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seoul-Anglican-Cathedral/ENP002030','The Seoul Anglican Cathedral was built during the Japanese colonial era and it is located beside Deoksugung Palace. The cathedral was constructed under the direction of the Rt. Reverend Mark Trollope, the third bishop of the Anglican Church of Korea and British architect Arthur Dixon. Although construction was completed in 1926, the Anglican Church of Korea considers 1890 as the date of the cathedral\'s foundation, since this was the year when the first service of Holy Communion was held. The cathedral is the seat of the Seoul Anglican Diocese and Tangible Cultural Property of Seoul No. 35.','-7261','Daily 11:00 - 16:00','Closed Weekends','100-120  15, Sejong-daero 21-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1 & 2, City Hall Station, Exit 3 (195m, 3-minute walk)','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67653&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67654&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67655&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.567129,'ENP002030'),
(65,'Yanghwajin Foreign Missionary Cemetery','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Yanghwajin-Foreign-Missionary-Cemetery/ENP001153','Yanghwajin Foreign Missionary Cemetery is the final resting place for Korea\'s western residents, including Dr. Horace Allen, the first director of Gwanghyewon, the first western-style hospital in Korea, founded in 1885. The cemetery is known as Foreign Missionary Cemetery because of the number of foreign missionaries buried here. Tombs and headstones were built in a western style creating an exotic atmosphere. The cemetery is located near the Hangang (River), an ideal spot for taking a pleasant stroll.      Yanghwajin Foreigners\' Cemetery is situated on the other side of Yanghwajin, opposite the martyrs??shrine. It is regarded as a Protestant shrine because many Protestant missionaries are buried there.  The ??00th Anniversary Memorial Church??was established in Yanhwajin by the ??Council for the 100th Anniversary of the Korean Church??to commemorate a century of missionary work in Korea.       Many of the foreigners who have contributed to the story of modern Korean history are buried in the Yanghwajin cemetery, such as Thomas Bethell, the founder of Daehan Maeil Sinbo (Newspaper); Mary Scranton, the founder of Ewha Hakdang (a mission school for girls, now Ewha Womans University); and Henry Appenzeller, the founder of Chungdong First Methodist Church.      A guided tour in English or Japanese is available in Yanghwajin Foreign Missionary Cemetery when booked in advance. These are conducted four times a day (10:00, 11:30, 14:00, 15:30) except during the New Year\'s holiday, Chuseok holiday and on Christmas day.       Yanghwajin Foreign Missionary Cemetery is located in Hapjeong-dong, Mapo-gu. It is a haven for foreign missionaries and their families who loved, and wished to lie in, Korea. The cemetery is managed by 100th Anniversary Memorial Church and contains Mission Memorial Hall.','-9426','Daily 10:00 - 17:00 (KST)','Closed Sundays\n??Guided tours are not offered on Sundays, Jan. 1st, Lunar New Year, Chuseok, and Christmas','04084  46, Yanghwajin-gil, Mapo-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 2 /6  Hapjeong Station  Exit 7,  319m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13443&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13444&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13445&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72584&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72585&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.547333,'ENP001153'),
(66,'Namsangol Hanok Village','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Namsangol-Hanok-Village/ENP000276','Namsangol Hanok Village is a collection of five hanok (traditional Korean houses) from the Joseon Dynasty (1392-1910), recovered from different parts of the city and relocated to the northern foot of Namsan Mountain. The interiors of each of these five houses reflect owners from different walks of life, from the middle class to high government officials, noblemen and aristocrats. At Namsangol Hanok Village, visitors can see the hanok of important figures from the Joseon era including the house of Queen Yun\'s parents, who was the Queen Consort to King Sunjong, the 27th king of the Joseon Dynasty; the jaesil (study) of Yun Taekyeong, King Sunjong\'s father-in-law; the house of Min Yeong-hui, a relative of Empress Myeongseong; the house of Lee Seungeop, who was in charge of constructing Gyeongbokgung Palace and the house of Kim Chunyeong, a military official of the Joseon Dynasty. At the hanok village, international visitors can participate in traditional Korean activities such as archery and enjoy traditional Korean performances as well. Anyone who is curious about Korean wedding culture should visit the village on the weekend when traditional wedding ceremonies take place.   { \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\", \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\", \"name\": \"Namsangol Hanok Village\", \"aggregateRating\": { \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\", \"ratingValue\": \"4.0\", \"ratingCount\": \"851\" }, \"review\": [{ \"@type\": \"Review\", \"reviewRating\": { \"@type\": \"Rating\", \"ratingValue\": \"5\" }, \"author\": { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"blanca\" }, \"reviewBody\": \"absolutely beautiful, and sometimes there are special performances so check the date before you visit for a fun extra!\", \"datePublished\": \"2023-10-22\" }] }','-11811','Summer season (April to October) 09:00 - 21:00 KST\nWinter season (November to March) 09:00 - 20:00 KST','Closed Mondays','04626  28, Toegye-ro 34-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul  Namsangol Hanok Village','Subway Lines 3/4  Chungmuro Station  Exit 4,  120m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68269&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68270&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68271&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68272&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66763&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.559315,'ENP000276'),
(67,'Seoul National Cemetery','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seoul-National-Cemetery/ENP001965','Seoul National Cemetery is the resting place of fallen Korean patriots. The cemetery was established to honor the loyalty and devotion of those who sacrificed and lived for their country. Facilities at the cemetary include the War History Museum, Memorial Tower, Memorial Hall, and the Altar to Patriots and Patriotic Martyrs. Memorial services are held yearly on June 6th, which marks the Korean Memorial Day holiday.','1522-1555','Daily 06:00 - 18:00 (Front gate, central gate, and other 5 gates)\n09:00 - 16:00 (Business facilities opening hours)','','06984  210, Hyeonchung-ro (Dongjak-dong), Dongjak-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4/9  Dongjak Station  Exit 4,  62m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49145&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49147&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49150&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49151&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49152&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.502263,'ENP001965'),
(68,'Myeongdong Cathedral','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Myeongdong-Cathedral/ENP004036','Myeongdong Cathedral is the very first Roman Catholic parish church in Korea. It is also the first Gothic building ever built in Korea and was designated as Historic site No. 285 in Korea. On the basement floor, there is a small sanctuary where the remains of the martyrs are enshrined, and where visitors to the cathedral can pay their respects. Every May, Myeongdong Cathedral holds a cultural festival. The construction of the cathedral started in 1892 and was completed in 1898. Unlike most Gothic buildings, Myeongdong Cathedral was built with bricks instead of stones. It gives the cathedral a characteristic atmosphere. The splendid high ceilings inside the church and the arches in between the magnificent inner pillars show the beautiful Gothic style well. The basement contains the remains of nine saints and martyrs, who devoted their lives to the propagation of Catholicism in Korea. Behind the cathedral, Seongmo Dongsan (St. Mary\'s garden) is situated. During lunch hour, pipe organs are playing here. The garden offers a peaceful resting space after visiting the cathedral.','-2478','','Closed Mondays','100-022  74, Myeongdong-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4, Myeong-dong Station, Exit 8, 590m\nSubway Line 2, Euljiro 1(il)-ga Station, Exit 5, 616m\nSubway Line 2, Euljiro 3(sam)-ga Station, Exit 12, 561m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68292&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68293&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68294&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68295&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73596&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.563079,'ENP004036'),
(69,'An Jung-geun Memorial Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/An-Jung-geun-Memorial-Hall/ENP004281','The An Jung-geun Memorial Hall was established to memorialize the Korean patriot An Jung-geun. An fought for Korean independence from Japan and was ultimately executed by Japanese authorities for assassinating Ito Hirobumi in 1909. Ito was a major force behind the Japanese annexation of Korea. The memorial hall is composed of 12 exhibition halls and galleries, an auditorium, a reference library, and a rest area. In addition to exhibition information about An\'s life and some of his calligraphy, the memorial hall also hosts the An Jung-guen Academny and other events each year. Events include visits to historic sites abroad that were important to independence movements and calligraphy contests. Admission to the An Jung-geun Memorial Hall is free.       { \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\", \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\", \"name\": \"An Jung-geun Memorial Hall\", \"aggregateRating\": { \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\", \"ratingValue\": \"4.0\", \"ratingCount\": \"26\" }, \"review\": { \"@type\": \"Review\", \"reviewRating\": { \"@type\": \"Rating\", \"ratingValue\": \"5\" }, \"author\": { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"travelsafer\" }, \"reviewBody\": \"This is a very touching museum dedicated to the life of an important Korean martyr who opposed the Japanese rule on the peninsula and ended up killing the Japanese price ruling over Korea. It is a testimony of the struggle of the oppressed people and symbolizes the will of Korea to be free and be ready for anything to reach its independence. I confess that, before visiting this place, I did not know anything about Ahn Jung Geun, but when I got out of the museum I felt quite emotional. His life is narrated as a story of strong belief and resistance until martyrdom. Many parts and panels are in Korean only, but the friendly lady at the entrance and a man who we met on the second floor were very helpful. In particular he gave us a small book in English about his life and pictures. If you can, add this museum to your list of place to visit in Seoul.\", \"datePublished\": \"2016-11-18\" } }] }','-4725','March to October: 10:00 - 18:00\nNovember to February: 10:00 - 17:00 (KST)','Closed Mondays, New Year\'s Day, Lunar New Year\'s Day & Chuseok','04636  91, Sowol-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Hoehyeon Station  Exit 3,  689m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17277&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17278&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17279&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=17280&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74159&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.554261,'ENP004281'),
(70,'Hyosa-gil in Heukseok-dong','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Hyosa-gil-in-Heukseok-dong-/ENP011112','Hyosa-gil in Heukseok-dong is a neighborhood where the architecture and atmosphere of 1960s and 1970s Korea is still intact. At the neighborhood\'s observatory, Seoul landmarks such as the Mapodaegyo Bridge, Hangangdaegyo Bridge, and Namsan Seoul Tower are visible. The observatory is a great vantage point for night views of Seoul and the annual Seoul International Fireworks Festival.','','','','06910   4, Hyosa-gil, 5-gil, Heukseok-dong, Dongjak-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 9  Heukseok Station  Exit 4,  702m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23359&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23360&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23361&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23362&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23363&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.535856,'ENP011112'),
(71,'Sukjeongmun Gate','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Sukjeongmun-Gate/ENP023760','Sukjeongmun Gate is one of Seoul??s four historic great city gates. It is the city\'s northern gate and it can be visited today along the Hanyangdoseong, Seoul City Wall. Cheong Wa Dae, the official residence of the South Korean president is located not far from the gate and city wall. For decades, public access to the gate and its section of the city wall was restricted for security reasons. In 2006, public access to this section of the Hanyangdoseong was restored and it is now a very popular hiking destination. On January 21st, 1963, Sukjeongmun was recognized as part of the Hanyangdoseong, Seoul City Wall and designated Historic Site No. 10.','-2819','*March to October (Daily): 09:00 - 18:00 (Last entry at 16:00)\n*Daily - November to February (Daily): 10:00 - 17:00 (Last entry at 15:00)','Closed Mondays','03049  1, Daesagwan-ro, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3, Gyeongbokgung Station, exit 3, take Blue Bus 710 at the Seoul Police Agency/Gyeongbokgung Station stop. Get off at Korea National Open University/Ihwajang, stop, and transfer to Green Bus 2112. Get off at Seoul Dawon School/Han Yong-un Acti','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22970&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22971&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22972&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22973&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22974&fileTy=MEDI',6.000000,37.599426,'ENP023760'),
(72,'Yeonghwiwon and Sunginwon Royal Tombs','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Yeonghwiwon-and-Sunginwon-Royal-Tombs/ENP004524','Yeonghwiwon and Sunginwon are the burial site of members of the Korean royal family and the site was designated Historic Site No. 361 in 1991. Yeonghwiwon is the royal tomb of Princess Consort Sunheon, wife of the 26th king of the Joseon Dynasty, Gojong. Sunginwon is the burial place of Crown Prince Yi Jin, grandson of King Gojong and Princess Consort Sunheon.       In Korea, tombs for kings and queens are traditionally called ??neung??and tombs of princes and royal consorts are called ??won?? Yeonghwiwon and Sunginwon were once known as Hongneung as Queen Myeongseong, the first wife of King Gojong was entombed here. The grave was moved to Geumgok-dong in the city of Namyangju in 1919 following the death of King Gojong. Since then, the site has been known as Yeonghwiwon and Sunginwon. Apart from its historic significance, the greenery and beautiful surroundings here have always attracted sightseers.','-1438','* November to January: 09:00 - 17:30 (KST)\n(Ticket booth 09:00 - 16:30 (KST))\n* February-May & September-October: 09:00 - 18:00 (KST)\n (Ticket booth 09:00 - 17:00 (KST))\n* June-August: 09:00 - 18:30 (KST)\n(Ticket booth 09:00 - 17:30 (KST))','Closed Mondays','02456  90, Hongneung-ro, Dongdaemun-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/ Gyeongui-Jungang Line/ Suin-Bundang Line  Cheongnyangni Station  Exit 2,  884m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68711&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68712&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68713&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68714&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.590035,'ENP004524'),
(73,'Guam Park','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Guam-Park/ENP002027','Guam Park is located in Gayang-dong, Seoul. The neighborhood is the birthplace of Heo Jun, a famous Joseon-era doctor and scholar. Next to the park is a museum dedicated to Heo Jun. His name is known in Korea to this day, more than 4 centuries after his death, in part because of his definitive text on Oriental medicine, \"Dongui Bogam.\" There is a large, shrubby rock big enough to accomodate 20 people in the park. Known as Heogabawi Rock, during times of conflict such as the Imjin War and the Second Manchu Invasion of Korea, the rock was used as a refuge.','-6632','','','07525  42, Heojun-ro 5-gil, Gangseo-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 9 Gayang Station Exit 1 , 741m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16126&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16127&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16128&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16129&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.567782,'ENP002027'),
(74,'Old Seoul Engineering School Main Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Old-Seoul-Engineering-School-Main-Hall/ENP003387','The Old Seoul Engineering School Main Hall (formerly known as the Central Laboratory Complex) was built in 1906 and designated Historic Site No. 289 in 1981. The building was designed by the national Architecture Bureau. While in use as a school, students were taught how to use modern technologies and skills such as dyeing, weaving, papermaking, goldsmithing and woodworking. The building now functions as a museum and is part of Korea National Open University.','1577-9995','Please refer to the website.','','03087  86, Daehak-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Hyehwa Station  Exit 2,  237m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12332&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12333&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12334&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.578828,'ENP003387'),
(75,'Maehun Yun Bong-Gil Memorial Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Maehun-Yun-Bong-Gil-Memorial-Hall/ENP003759','The Maehun Yun Bong-Gil Memorial Hall is dedicated to the resistance fighter, Patriot Yun Bong-gil. Yun\'s pen name was Maehun and he was active in the Korean independence movement during the Japanese colonial era. Located in Seoul\'s Yangjae dong, the first floor of the memorial is an exhibition hall that displays relics and biographical information about Yun Bong-gil in chronological order. On the second floor, the exhibition hall contains photographs and other materials of the Korean independence movement organized by theme. Admission to the memorial hall is free.','-3886','* April to October: 10:00 - 18:00\n* November to March: 10:00 - 17:00\n??Last entry is 30 mins prior to closing','Closed Mondays, New Year\'s Day, Lunar New Year??s Day & Chuseok','06773   99, Maeheon-ro, Seocho-gu, Seoul','Subway Sinbundang Line  Yangjae Citizen\'s Forest Station  Exit 5,  179m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=2255&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=2257&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=2258&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74827&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74828&fileTy=MEDIA&f',5.000000,37.470220,'ENP003759'),
(76,'Baek In-je House','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Baek-Injes-House/ENP021128','The Baek Inje??s House, located in Gahoe-dong, Bukchon, is a representative traditional house that well preserves the style of modern hanok architecture. Although built during the Japanese occupation period, it has been designated as a Seoul Metropolitan Folklore Cultural Heritage due to its good condition and its blend of traditional hanok beauty with modern adaptations. Situated on a plot overlooking Bukchon, the property features a spacious Anchae (main living quarters) and a large garden centered around the Sarangchae (men\'s quarters), with a small Byeoldangchae (detached quarters) on the highest point. In this quiet, traditional setting, visitors can glimpse the lifestyle of the wealthy class of that era and observe features that distinguish it from typical upper-class homes of the time. Detailed information on the Baek Inje??s House, including its history, context, and characteristics, is available in the Haengnangchae (servants\' quarters) and small Sarangbang (guest reception room). While general tours don\'t require reservations, entry to some areas like the Sarangchae and Byeoldangchae is only for those with guided tour bookings.   ??Baek In-je (1898 - Unknown): Baek In-je was a Korean patriot who fought for Korean independence during the Japanese colonial era. Baek was also a doctor who devoted much of his time to studying rickets and blood disorders. He made great contributions to the body of research on these medical issues.','+82-2-724-0200,0200','09:00-18:00 (Last entry at 17:30)\n??Visitors not on a guided tour may only tour the grounds \n??Fridays & Saturdays until 20:00 during August','Closed Mondays & New Year\'s Day','03055  16, Bukchon-ro 7-gil (Gahoe-dong), Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 2,  464m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68028&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20050&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20052&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=14800&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.580804,'ENP021128'),
(77,'Jeongdong-gil','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Jeongdong-gil/ENP000889','Mentioning Jeongdong-gil brings up a couple of imageries: old town neighborhoods, relaxing streets not crowded with people, a peaceful place to take a stroll, and so on. While all the above are true, visitors should also be aware that Jeongdong-gil is full of many historic buildings that managed to survive through Korea\'s turbulent past. It is also a place close to a lot of embassies like the Russian Embassy, British Embassy, US Embassy, German Embassy, etc. Chungdong First Methodist Church and Ewha Girls\' High School are some of the facilities which were built in the earlier era. A century later, Jeongdong-gil has been reborn as a cultural street featuring Seoul Museum of Art, Jeongdong Theater, and many other historical and cultural facilities and attractions.','-40','','','04516  2, Jeongdong-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 1/2  City Hall Station  Exit 12,  580m \nSubway Line 5  Seodaemun Station  Exits 5,  581m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69082&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69083&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69084&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69085&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.568026,'ENP000889'),
(78,'April 19th National Cemetery','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/April-19th-National-Cemetery/ENP027106','With Bukhansan Mountain as its backdrop, the April 19th National Cemetery is a memorial ground for the people who??ve lost their lives in the April 19th Revolution. Inside the cemetery, there??s a white memorial tower erected in memory of these people and an exhibition hall and memorial hall displaying the events of the April 19th Revolution.','-1335','National Cemetery\n* March - October 06:00 - 18:00\n* November - February 07:00 - 18:00\n\nMemorial Hall\n* March - October 09:30 - 17:30\n* November - February 09:30 - 16:30','* National Cemetery: Open year round\n* Memorial Hall: Closed Mondays','01009  17, 4.19-ro 8-gil, Gangbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4, Suyu Station, Exits 2 & 6','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20502&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20505&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20503&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=20504&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.648936,'ENP027106'),
(79,'Gyeonggyojang','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Gyeonggyojang/ENP001151','Gyeonggyojang is an historic site that was the headquarters of the Provisional Korean Government during the Japanese colonial era and the private residence of Kim Koo. Kim Koo was a writer (using the pen name Baekbeom), independence activist and politician who served as the last premier of the Provisional Korean Government. He lived, worked, and ultimately died at Gyeonggyojang at the hands of an assassin. Kim was an immensely influential figure in Korean history and remains deeply revered to this day. Visitors to Gyeonggyojang can learn more about Kim Koo and the Korean independence movement.','-2693','Daily 09:00 - 18:00 KST','Closed Mondays & January 1','03181  29, Saemunan-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 5  Seodaemun Station  Exit 4,  325m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68162&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68163&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68167&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68168&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.567292,'ENP001151'),
(80,'Jeon Tae-il Memorial Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Jeon-Tae-il-Memorial-Hall/ENP034860','Having been built by the Seoul city government, the Jeon Tae-il Memorial Hall is a labor complex facility erected to illuminate upon the historical significance of Jeon Tae-il, whose self-sacrifice served as a pivotal point in time in the history of the Korean labor movement. The young man gave everything he had to create a world that centered itself around the mentality that workers are people that have the right to live, work, and study in good health. In order to help bring Jeon Tae-il\'s dream into fruition, the hall urges unity between the labor force, the youth of the country, and the public, brought together around the ideals of love and solidarity.','-1141','March - October 10:00 - 18:00\nNovember - February 10:00 - 17:30','Closed Mondays, January 1 & holidays','03191  105, Cheonggyecheon-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 2/3  Euljiro 3(sam)-ga Station  Exit 2,  362m \nSubway Line 1/3/5  Jongno 3(sam)-ga Station  Exit 15,  373m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=32054&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=32055&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=32056&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75400&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75401&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.569160,'ENP034860'),
(81,'Dosan Park','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Dosan-Park/ENP001789','Dosan Park is a large public park that was established to commemorate Dosan Ahn Chang-ho. Ahn is widely revered in Korea for his patriotism and achievements as an educator. He wrote under the pen name Dosan and was an independence activist, political reformer, and educator. The park features a statue of Ahn Chang-ho as well as a memorial hall dedicated to his memory. At the Dosan Ahn Chang-ho Memorial Hall, visitors can learn more about the life, writings, and achievements of Ahn Chang-ho.    Dosan Park has become a must-visit destination in Gangnam. It is surrounded by numerous restaurants, cafes, galleries, and clothing shops. Additionally, the area features flagship stores of renowned international brands, making it an excellent spot for shopping.','-9588','Dosan Ahn Chang-ho Memorial Hall: Open daily from 10:00 to 18:00','','06020  20, Dosan-daero 45-gil, Gangnam-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3, Apgujeong Station, Exits 2 & 3, 882m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60065&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60066&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=5&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68282&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68283&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68284&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.524390,'ENP001789'),
(82,'Sajikdan (Sajik Altar)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Sajikdan-Sajik-Altar/ENP001824','Sajikdan (Sajik Altar) is an altar built during Joseon Dynasty that was used to pray to the gods for a good harvest. The altar is located in Sajik Park and in addition to the altar, visitors can see the Hwanghakjeong Archery Range and the Dangunseongjeon Shrine. The Jongno Public Library and a children\'s library is also located nearby.','-7864','','','03027  89, Sajik-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 1,  337m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68722&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68723&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68724&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68726&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68727&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.576969,'ENP001824'),
(83,'Seokguram','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-seokguram/ENPexzzw3','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}Seokguram Grotto is nestled halfway up Inwangsan Mountain, just below Chimabawi Rock, and can be reached via the Inwangsan Mountain Trail. Inside, you\'ll find the Three Buddha Statues, while the surrounding forest path features a Buddha statue and a Maitreya Buddha carved into the rocks. Above the main hall at Sanshingak Shrine, a large rock bears a painting of the Mountain Spirit and a tiger that guards Inwangsan. About 30 meters to the right of Seokguram, you can also visit the Cheonhyangam Hermitage. From Seokguram, you\'ll enjoy stunning panoramic views of Seoul, with Namsan Tower visible on the opposite mountain and, on clear days, even Lotte Tower. Below, Gyeongbokgung Palace and the Blue House come into view.','-2058','','','03034  3-14, Ogin-dong, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 2,  1.7km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67174&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67176&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67177&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67178&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73923&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.582083,'ENPexzzw3'),
(84,'Site of Concubine Jang Huibin??s Well','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-jangheebin/ENPcyd45f','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}The area of the Site of Concubine Jang Huibin??s Well has been associated with Yeonhui Palace, a detached palace since the early Joseon Dynasty. It has been associated with palace grounds, courtyards, main buildings, and the royal family\'s first mulberry orchard. It has been passed down by the name Seojamsil, known as the Site of Concubine Jang Huibin??s Well.The first palace in this area was used as a refuge palace by King Jeongjong, who abdicated the throne to his younger brother, King Taejong, in the 3rd year of King Jeongjong\'s reign (1400). Later, in August of the 7th year of King Sejong\'s reign (1425), the palace was renamed Yeonhui Palace. It is said that there were wells in various places within the palace grounds due to the presence of palace officials and palace women. Among them, the preserved well is called the Site of Concubine Jang Huibin??s Well.During the reign of King Sukjong (1674-1720), Huibin Jang (1659-1701), who followed Queen Inhyeon, who was deposed, briefly stayed at this place as a concubine, but there is no proof she drank from the well. Over time, oral tradition in Yeonhui-dong has perpetuated the belief that \"this well is where Huibin Jang drank water,\" upheld by generations of elders. Consequently, it was chosen for restoration as a part of the community\'s treasure-hunting initiative.','','','','03702  74 Yeonhui-ro 15-gil, Seodaemun-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 2 / Gyeongui Central Line/ Airport Railroad  Hongik University Station  Exit3,  1.6km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=64823&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=64824&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',2.000000,37.571095,'ENPcyd45f'),
(85,'Jeongneung (A Royal Tomb)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Jeongneung-A-Royal-Tomb1/ENP003459','Jeongneung is the royal tomb of Queen Sindeok. She was the second wife of King Taejo, the founder of the Joseon Dynasty. It is said that the tomb was originally located behind Deoksugong (Palace) but moved to the current location when a son of King Taejo\'s first wife, King Taejong ( the third king of the Joseon Dynasty) ascended the throne. The original scale of the tomb was reduced as well. Although it is a simple tomb without many of the stone figures traditionally placed before a royal tomb, it has historical interest as it has faithfully kept the style of an early Joseon period tomb. The tomb is in picturesque surrounds with Bukhansan National Park located nearby.','-5967','February - May & September - October 06:00 - 18:00\nJune - August 06:00 - 18:30\nNovember - January 06:30 - 17:30\n* Ticket booth closes 1 hour prior to closing.','Closed Mondays','136-100  116, Arirang-ro 19-gil, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Ui-Sinseol Line  Jeongneung Station  Exit 2,  584m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72663&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72664&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72665&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72666&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72667&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.601215,'ENP003459'),
(86,'Seokpajeong','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seokpajeong/ENP037164','The name of this historical complex, \"Seokpachon,\" translates into English as \"surrounded by water, soaring above the clouds\" and was given in honor of the great Heungseon Daewongun, the regent of the Joseon Kingdom. The Seokpachon complex is more than 600 years old, but it has been able to maintain its original appearance through careful preservation. This place is remarkable for its extraordinary beauty and it displays a combination of traditional Korean and Chinese architecture. This historic garden is currently under the authority of the Seoul Museum, which celebrates traditional and contemporary Korean art throughout the world.','-415','10:00 - 18:00 (Admission closes at 16:00)','Monday and Tuesday\n(??Closed Feb 26-May 31 for internal construction and next exhibition.)','03021  4-1 Changimun-ro 11-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3   Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 3,  take bus 1020, 1711, 7016, 7018, get off at Jahamun Tunnel Entrance','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=41310&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=41311&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=41312&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.597216,'ENP037164'),
(87,'Gyeongbokgung Palace Jibokjae','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-Jibokjae/ENPfk9nxi','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}This building is located to the west of Geoncheonggung in Gyeongbokgung Palace. It housed about 40,000 books on Western artifacts purchased from the Qing Dynasty and was mainly used as King Gojong??s private library. Additionally, it served as a venue for enshrining portraits of kings or receiving foreign envoys. Originally constructed as a secondary building of Hamnyeongjeon Hall in Changdeokgung, it was relocated to Gyeongbokgung in 1891. The building was opened to the public in 2006, and the books previously housed there are now kept at Seoul National University\'s Kyujanggak Institute for Korean Studies and the Jangseogak Archives of the Academy of Korean Studies. In 2016, Jibokjae was transformed into a library and opened to the public. It is open from April to October, except for July and August, making it a great place to visit if you\'re in Gyeongbokgung during this period.','-12092','10:00 ~ 16:00','Tuesdays','03045  161 Sajik-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 5,  1.1km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67952&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67951&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67950&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67949&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.580847,'ENPfk9nxi'),
(88,'Salgoji Bridge (Jeongotgyo Bridge)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Salgoji-Bridge-Jeongotgyo-Bridge/ENP002372','Salgoji Bridge (Jeongotgyo Bridge) is a historic stone bridge that dates back to the Joseon Dynasty. It stands over point where Cheonggyecheon and Jungangcheon Streams meet the Hangang River. It is the longest bridge from the Joseon era and was first designated Historic Site No. 160 in 1967; then elevated to Treasure No. 1738 in 2011. The bridge stands not far from Hanyang University.','-7410','','','61-1 Haengdang-dong, Seongdong-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 2  Hanyang University Station  Exit 3,  257m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12270&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12271&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12272&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12273&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75706&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.554082,'ENP002372'),
(89,'Comfort Women Memorial','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Comfort-Women-Memorial/ENP019540','The Comfort Women Memorial is located in Namsan, Yejang-dong, Jung-gu, Seoul, and opened in 2016. It serves as a memorial park honoring the victims and survivors of the Japanese military??s wartime sexual slavery. The space is centered around their testimonies, records of victimization, and documentation of Japan??s war crimes, embodying the themes of human rights and peace.','','','','04628  6, Toegye-ro 26ga-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Myeong-dong Station  Exit 1,  511m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13024&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13025&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13026&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74172&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74173&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.558461,'ENP019540'),
(90,'Sungkyunkwan University\'s Myeongryundang Lecture Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Sungkyunkwan-Universitys-Myeongryundang-Lecture-Hall/ENP003176','Sungkyunkwan University was originally founded centuries ago during the Joseon Dynasty. Myeongryundang Lecture Hall is one of the Joseon era buildings that can still be seen at the university\'s Seoul campus. In the lecture hall\'s courtyard is a beautiful ginko tree that is thought to be more than 500 years old. The tree is known for its beauty and was designated Natural Monument No. 59.       Frequently Asked Questions about Sungkyunkwan University\'s Myeongryundang Lecture Hall         Is there an entrance fee for the Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall?         The Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall entrance is free.          Is the Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall always open?         The Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall opening hours are as follows. (As of 2024)     ??Summer season(March to October) : 09:00~18:00   ??Winter season(November to February) : 09:00~17:00       { \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\", \"@type\": \"FAQPage\", \"mainEntity\": [{ \"@type\": \"Question\", \"name\": \"Is there an entrance fee for the Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall?\", \"acceptedAnswer\": { \"@type\": \"Answer\", \"text\": \"<div> The Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall entrance is free. </div>\" } }, { \"@type\": \"Question\", \"name\": \"Is the Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall always open?\", \"acceptedAnswer\": { \"@type\": \"Answer\", \"text\": \"<div> The Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall opening hours are as follows. (As of 2024)<br><br> <ul> <li>Summer season(March to October) : 09:00~18:00</li> <li>Winter season(November to February) : 09:00~17:00</li> </ul> </div>\" } }, { \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\", \"name\": \"the Sungkyunkwan Myeongnyundang Lecture Hall\", \"aggregateRating\": { \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\", \"ratingValue\": \"4\", \"ratingCount\": \"12\" }, \"review\": { \"@type\": \"Review\", \"reviewRating\": { \"@type\": \"Rating\", \"ratingValue\": \"5\" }, \"author\": { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"Alice C\" }, \"reviewBody\": \"The current Seonggyungwan University in Seoul has a long history. Back in Joseon Dynasty, the highest national academy is this very monument. You can still see the seminar hall and the housing quarters for the students in ancient time. The giant ginko tree has been designated a Natural Monument in Korea. The monument is a photo spot especially during autumn. Many university students like to take their graduation photos in this ancient monument too.\", \"datePublished\": \"2016-08-21\" } }] }','-2152','Summer (March - October): 09:00 - 18:00\n Winter (November - February): 09:00 - 17:00','','110-812  25-1, Sungkyunkwan-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Hyehwa Station  Exit 4,  833m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=13365&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69077&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69078&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69079&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=69080&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.588227,'ENP003176'),
(91,'Shina Memorial Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-shina/ENPjkm9y3','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}Located in Jeong-dong, this building is notable for its uniquely stacked red bricks. It was constructed in the 1930s as a reinforced concrete building with one basement level and two above-ground floors. The structure, finishes, and facilities reflect its nearly 100-year history. Initially used as the Korean branch of the American sewing machine brand ??Singer,??it was purchased by Shina Ilbo, Korea\'s first commercial newspaper, in 1963. Shina Ilbo expanded the building by adding the third and fourth floors in 1975, using it as an annex. Following the forced shutdown of Shina Ilbo, the building was transformed into a memorial to commemorate the founder, Jang Ki-bong, and the newspaper. Today, it houses various businesses, including memorial halls, a café, and boutique shops, on each floor.','-10572','Vary by company','','04518  33 Jeongdong-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/2  City Hall Station  Exit 12,  507m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66423&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66424&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66425&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66426&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.567123,'ENPjkm9y3'),
(92,'Jungnang Mang-u Space','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Jungnang-Mang-u-Space/ENP041904','Manguri, which was used as a cemetery for a long time, it was reborn as a Mang-U History & Culture Park to honor the spirits of the activists for independence such as Yu Gwan-sun, Han Yong-un, Ahn Chang-ho and Bang Jeong-hwan. Jungnang Mang-u Space is where the place newly created to honor a sublime meaning of great men by walking a calm nature of Mangusan Mountain. Jungnang Mang-u Space consists of the two buildings, a managing building and an exhibition building. A managing building administers the areas of grave and runs memorial ceremony. At an exhibition building, the works of literary people who are enshrined in Manguri, are being exhibited.','+82-2-496-8974~6','Monday to Friday 09:00-18:00','','02178  2, Mangu-ro 91-gil, Jungnang-gu, Seoul','Subway Gyeongui-Jungang Line  Yangwon Station  Exit 2,  1.5km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=54704&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=54705&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=54706&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=54707&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=54708&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.597085,'ENP041904'),
(93,'Bongeunsa Temple','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Bongeunsa/ENP000411','Bongeunsa is a Buddhist temple founded in 794 during the Silla (one of the Three Kingdoms of Korea) period. The temple has more than 1,000 years of history and has many interesting historic and cultural features, including woodblock carvings of the Avatamsaka Sutra (Flower Garland Sutra). The temple is also a very popular tourist destination, offering various programs relating to traditional Korean Buddhist culture, in a variety of languages.       Bongeunsa is more than a just temple. It provides a place to relax for busy city people and also gives people a chance to reflect upon themselves. The templestay program gives an opportunity to experience everyday life in the temple, which includes traditional Korean Buddhist culture and practices. Visitors can experience some simple Buddhist practices such as the daily dawn service, Korean Zen meditation, Dado (a tea drinking ceremony), and Balwoogongyang (a Buddhist meal with traditional bowls).  Every May on Buddha\'s birthday, Bongeunsa holds the Lotus Lantern Festival on nearby Samseong-don   g.','-7938','','','06087  531, Bongeunsa-ro, Gangnam-gu, Seoul, Korea','Subway Line 9  Bongeunsa Station  Exit 1,  135m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60965&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60966&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60967&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60968&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60969&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.514902,'ENP000411'),
(94,'Pungnaptoseong Fortress','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Pungnaptoseong-Fortress/ENP001953','Pungnaptoseong Fortress is the site of earthen ramparts that date back to the Baekje period (18 BCE-660 AD). Because many pieces of pottery have been uncovered here during excavations, it is thought that the site may have been a residential area at one time. Another important Baekje site, Mongchontoseong Fortress is located nearby.','-4867','','','05512  30, Hangaram-ro 20-gil, Songpa-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 5/8  Cheonho Station  Exit 9,  127m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12499&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12500&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12501&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12502&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74825&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.538690,'ENP001953'),
(95,'Bangi-dong Ancient Baekje Tombs','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Bangi-dong-Ancient-Baekje-Tombs/ENP002544','The Bangi-dong Ancient Baekje Tombs are ancient tombs in located the Bangi-dong area that date back to the Hanseong Baekje era. The ancient Hanseong Baekje Kingdom was founded along the Hangang River in 18 BCE and lasted for nearly 5 centuries. The tombs were discovered in the 1970s during the Jamsil District Zoning Project and there are 8 tombs altogether. Unfortunately, most of the artifacts were stolen at some point in time, but the tombs themselves were preserved well. Visitors can observe the original structures of the tombs and learn more about Hanseong Baekje. These ancient tombs are an important historical site and the area around the tombs was made into a park. There are paths between the tombs and visitors can take a quiet walk around the park and observe the tombs while enjoying the park\'s fresh air and grass. The site holds the designation of Historic Site No. 270.','-4881','Daily 09:00 ??20:00\n* Winter Season 09:00 ??19:00','','05644  219, Ogeum-ro, Songpa-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 5 Bangi Station Exit 3, 600m\nSubway Line 9 Songpanaru Station Exit 3, 613m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16452&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16453&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16454&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16455&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73692&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.508377,'ENP002544'),
(96,'Jogyesa Temple','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Jogyesa-Temple/ENP002586','Jogyesa Temple was established in 1910 under the name Gakhwangsa by monks who aspired for the independence of Korean Buddhism and the restoration of the national capital. At the time, Gakhwangsa was the first temple to be situated within the four main gates of Seoul. In 1937, efforts began to relocate Gakhwangsa to its present site, now known as Jogyesa. Positioned in the heart of Jongno, Seoul, it is the only traditional temple in the city center, offering a place for visitors to rest. The temple grounds are open 24/7, welcoming locals and foreigners anytime. The temple hosts a temple stay program and the annual Lotus Lantern Festival.','-9288','Opening hours vary depending on what Buddhist ceremonies are taking place and the temple schedule','','03144  55, Ujeongguk-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 1  Jonggak Station  Exit 2,  413m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72645&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72646&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72647&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72648&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72649&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.574039,'ENP002586'),
(97,'Manhae Han Yong-Un Simujang','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Manhae-Han-Yong-Un-Simujang/ENP001399','Simujang, the residence of Manhae Han Yong-un, was built in 1933 during the Japanese occupation. Unlike typical hanok homes that face south, this house faces north. As an independence activist, Manhae chose a north-facing site on the hillside to avoid facing the Japanese Government-General of Korea. The house has a rectangular layout with a hip-and-gable roof and features four front rooms and two side rooms. Inside, you??ll find Manhae\'s personal room with preserved artifacts such as his calligraphy, research papers, and court records from his time in prison. After his death, his only daughter, Han Young-sook, lived there. However, when the Japanese Embassy moved across from the property, she relocated to Myeongnyun-dong, and Simujang was transformed into a research center dedicated to Manhae\'s philosophy.','-4813','Daily 09:00 - 18:00 (KST)','Open year round','02879  24, Seongbuk-ro 29-gil, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Hansung University Station  Exit 6,  62 m  to the Samsun-gyo and Seongbuk Cultural Center bus stop. Take the Seongbuk 03 bus and get off at the Supermarket stop.  127m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68839&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68840&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68841&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68842&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.593621,'ENP001399'),
(98,'Wonhyoro Catholic Church','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Wonhyoro-Catholic-Church/ENP001862','Wonhyoro Catholic Church is located beside Sacred Heart Girls\' High School (once the Yongsan Seminary) and was consecrated in 1902. The church is small in scale but notable for its French Gothic architecture. Visitors to Seoul can visit an important piece of modern Korean history with a stop at Wonhyoro Catholic Church.','-6122','Daily 09:00 - 17:00','Hours may vary according to the school\'s schedule','04361  49, Wonhyo-ro 19-gil, Yongsan-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 6/Gyeongui Central   Hyochang Park Station  Exit 4,  1.3km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16661&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16662&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16663&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16664&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74171&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.534334,'ENP001862'),
(99,'A Look at Yonsei University\'s 3 Historic Halls','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Yonsei-Universitys-Stimson-Hall--Underwood-Hall--Appenzeller-Hall/ENP002435','Yonsei University is one of Korea\'s best universities. Its history is deep and many of the buildings on the Yonsei campus have modern historical significance as they were built in the early years of the 20th century. Stimson Hall was the first building ever built on the Yonsei campus and it was constructed in 1920. The hall was designated Historic Site No. 275 in 1981. Underwood Hall, Historic Site No. 276, was the second building ever built at Yonsei University. Today the hall functions as a museum dedicated to the founder of Yonsei, Horace G. Underwood and the Underwood family. Appenzeller Hall was built in 1924 and holds the designation of Historic Site No. 277. The hall was built to commemorate Henry Appenzeller who established the famed Korean boys\' school, Paichai Hakdang.','-4157','Daily 09:00 - 17:00','','03722  50, Yonsei-ro, Seodaemun-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 2  Sinchon Station  Exits 2,  1.2km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=1601&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=1602&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=1605&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.564699,'ENP002435'),
(100,'Grand Greenhouse Changgyeonggung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/GrandGreenhouseChanggyeonggungPalace/ENP037176','Changgyeonggung Palace, one of the four main historical palaces in Seoul, houses a greenhouse built in 1909. It is Korea\'s first greenhouse designed in a Western architectural style. Initially, there was a botanical garden and a zoo. In 2004, the building was restored, retaining the original appearance of the greenhouse, and is open to the public. Here you will find different types of plants, both local and imported from other countries.','-10197','09:00 - 20:45','Mondays','03072  185, Changgyeonggung-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul, Korea (창경???','Subway Line 4  Hyehwa Station  Exit 4,  779m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=40391&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=40393&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=40555&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74820&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74821&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.578815,'ENP037176'),
(101,'Taereung and Gangreung Royal Tombs','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Taereung-and-Gangreung-Royal-Tombs/ENP002299','Taereung and Gangneung Royal Tombs are the burial sites of royalty from the Joseon Dynasty. Located in Hwarang-dong, Taereung and Gangneung sit next to each other. The Korea National Training Center for Sports sits between the two royal tombs and the center is operated by the Korean Olympic Committee. Taereung is the royal tomb of Queen Munjeong; the second wife of the 11th Joseon king, Jungjong. Gangneung is the royal tomb of the Queen Munjeong\'s son and the 13th Joseon king, Myeongjong and his wife, Queen Insun. In June 2009, all 40 of the royal tombs of the Joseon Dynasty were designated UNESCO World Heritage sites.','-6536','* February to May, September & October: 09:00 - 18:00\n* June to August: 09:00 - 18:30\n* November to January: 09:00 - 17:30\n*Last entry 1 hour before closing','Closed Mondays','01794  681, Hwarang-ro, Nowon-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 6  Hwarangdae Station  Exit 4,  1.6km','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16323&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16324&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16325&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.634368,'ENP002299'),
(102,'Bosingak Pavilion (Bell Ringing Ceremony)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Bosingak-Pavilion-Bell-Ringing-Ceremony/ENP001904','Bosingak Pavilion, a bell tower located in Jongno 2-ga, Jongno-gu, was the original site of the Old Bronze Bell (Treasure No.2). Due to cracks that rendered the bell unringable, it is now housed at the National Museum of Korea in Yongsan. The current bell hanging in Bosingak Pavilion is a newly cast replica, funded through public donations. It was installed on August 14, 1985, and first rung the following day, August 15. Bosingak Pavilion is renowned for hosting Korea??s iconic New Year??s Eve bell-ringing ceremony, where the bell is struck 33 times at midnight on December 31. Additionally, the bell is rung 12 times daily at noon, except on Mondays.','-3036','Bosingak Pavillon Ringing Ceremony 11:00 ~ 12:30 (KST)\n* Reservation required for the bell ringing experience','Closed Mondays, March 1st, August 15th, and days with inclement weather','03189  54, Jong-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul  (Bosingak Pavilion)','Subway Line 1  Jonggak Station  Exit 4,  63m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49978&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49979&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49980&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49981&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=49985&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.569760,'ENP001904'),
(103,'Yakhyeon Catholic Church','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Yakhyeon-Catholic-Church/ENP001845','Yakhyeon Catholic Church was the first Western-style church ever built in Korea. Located in Jungnim-dong, the church can be seen from Seoullo 7017. Yakhyeon Catholic Church has historical significance as a religious site and its architecture was hugely influential on the architectural styles of other churches in Korea. The building was destroyed by fire in 1998 but it was subsequently restored.','-2173','* Museum 09:00 - 18:00\n* Gallery 09 :00 - 18:00\n\n* Mass Schedule:\nMondays 06:00\nTuesdays 19:00\nWednesdays 10:00\nThursdays 10:00, 19:00\nFridays 10:00 (Mass at Hyeonyangtap at Seosomun Martyrs\' Shrine in Seosomun Park)\nSaturdays 18:00 \nSundays 09:30, 11:00,','Museum: Closed Mondays, New Year\'s Day & Chuseok\nChurch: Closed to visitors during mass','04506  447-1, Cheongpa-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 2 / 5   Chungjeongno Station  Exit 4,  481m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68753&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68754&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68755&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74161&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.558854,'ENP001845'),
(104,'Wongudan Altar','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Wongudan-Altar/ENP004198','Wongudan was built during the Joseon Dynasty to be an altar for performing divine harvest rituals. Located in central Seoul right near City Hall, it was designated Historic Site No. 157 in 1967. Through the past few centuries the altar was once called Hwandan and more recently Hwangudan. Now officially known as Wongudan Altar, Wongudan is located in close proximity to other major Seoul tourist attractions so it\'s convenient and easy to add a stop to Wongudan on a Seoul travel itinerary. The current Hwangudan Altar is a complex established in 1897 on the site of the old Nambyeolgung Palace. Its altar was built for Emperor Gojong\'s enthronement ceremony and rituals. The Japanese demolished the original complex in 1913, and a railway hotel was built on the site, reducing its size. Today, only the Hwangungu, the stone drum, and a stone gate with three arches remain preserved within the grounds of the Joseon Hotel.','-9196','Daily 07:00 - 21:00','','100-070  106, Sogong-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/2  City Hall Station  Exit 6,  157m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68705&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68706&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68707&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68708&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68709&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.564438,'ENP004198'),
(105,'Seodaemun Prison History Hall','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seodaemun-Prison-History-Hall/ENP001831','Seodaemun Prison was used to intern Korean patriots during the Japanese occupation. Until the Liberation of Korea on August 15, 1945, it was known as a clandestine mecca for the anti-Japanese resistance fighters, where they were tortured and executed. The Seodaemun Prison History Hall opened in November 1998 in Seodaemun Independence Park to commemorate the patriots who sacrificed their lives in the fight for Korean independence during the Japanese occupation. It consists of a historic exhibition hall, a central prison, jail cells, a hospital, the patriot memorial, an execution room, a tunnel through which corpses were carried, a watchtower, and a basement jail cell where the female patriot, Yu Gwansun, was tortured and killed.','-8870','March - October 09:30 ??18:00\nNovember - February 09:30 ??17:00','Closed Mondays, Lunar New Year, January 1st & Chuseok','120-080  251, Tongil-ro, Seodaemun-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Dongnimmun Station  Exit 5,  209m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73784&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67724&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73785&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73786&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73787&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.574217,'ENP001831'),
(106,'Uireung','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Uireung/ENP005205','Uireung is the royal tomb of King Gyeongjong, the 20th king of the Joseon dynasty, and his wife Queen Seonui. Uireung is located inside the Korea National University of Arts campus in Seokgwan-dong, Seongbuk-gu. Most royal tombs are \"ssangneung,\" tombs that are arranged with the king and queen next to each other. At Uireung, the tombs of the king and the queen are arranged front to back. The tomb in the front is Queen Seonui??s and the one in the back belongs to King Gyeongjong. Uireung is closed Mondays.','-1463','* February - May & September - October 09:00 - 18:00 KST (Ticket office closes at 17:00 KST)\n* June - August 09:00 - 18:30 KST(Ticket office closes at 17:30 KST)\n* November - January 09:00 - 17:30 KST (Ticket office closes at 16:30 KST)','Closed Mondays','02789  146-37, Hwarang-ro 32-gil, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 1  Sinimun Station  Exit 1,  945m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=2971&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=2974&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=2975&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74829&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74830&fileTy=MEDIA&f',5.000000,37.606324,'ENP005205'),
(107,'Heonilleung','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Heonilleung/ENP005240','Heonilleung is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and the final resting place of two pairs of the Joseon Dynasty\'s kings and queens. The name of the site is a combination of the names of the two separate tombs, Heonleung and Inleung. The tombs of Joseon\'s third king, Taejong (1367-1422), and his wife, Queen Wongyeong (1365-1420) are at Heonleung. Inleung is the resting place of Joseon\'s 23rd king, Sunjo (1790-1834), and his wife Queen Sunwon (1789-1857). Heonilleung is unique in that it houses two kings born 400 years apart. Visitors to the royal tombs can see examples of early and late Joseon Dynasty royal tombs and there is a weekly talk about the tombs every Saturday. On Lunar New Year\'s Day, traditional performances are held at Heonilleung for the public to enjoy.','-712','* February - May & September - October 09:00 - 18:00 KST\n* June - August 09:00 - 18:30 KST\n* November - January 09:00 - 17:30 KST','Closed Mondays','06795  36-10, Heonilleung-gil, Seocho-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3, Yangjae Station, Exit 7. From the Yangjae Station - Seocho Cultural Arts Center bus stop 240m  board buses 440, 741, or 452 and get off at the Heonilleung??Gangnam Seocho Science Reserve Training Center stop. Heonilleung is 662m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23336&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23337&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23338&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23339&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=23340&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.470451,'ENP005240'),
(108,'Sodeokmun Gate (Seosomun)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Site-of-Sodeokmun-Gate-Seosomun/ENP023758','Sodeokmun Gate was one of the 4 minor city gates of Seoul. It was constructed during the Joseon Dynasty in the reign of King Taejong. Sodeokmun was torn down in 1914 during the Japanese colonial period under the pretext of ??urban planning.??No traces of Sodeokmun Gate remain today but a plaque marks the site of the gate.','-40','','','04513  100, Seosomun-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/2  City Hall Station  Exit 9,  300m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22980&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22981&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22982&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22983&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22984&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.561775,'ENP023758'),
(109,'Sayuksin Park','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Sayuksin-Park-EN/ENP004513','Sayuksin Park is located atop a hill between the Hangang River and Noryangjin Station. The park encompasses the historic Sayuksinmyo Tombs and the surrounding hilly area. The tombs hold the designation of Seoul Cultural Asset No. 8 and they are the burial site of seven Korean loyalists to the King Danjong, 6th king of the Joseon Dynasty. King Danjong was forced to abdicate by his uncle, who then assumed to the throne to become King Sejo. Seong Sam-Mun, Park Paeng-Nyeon, Ha Wi-Ji, Yi Gae, Yu Seong-Won, Yu Eung-Bu, and Kim Mun-Gi who opposed King Sejo and were buried here by the Hangang River.','-10584','Daily 09:00 - 18:00','','06902  191 Noryangjin-ro, Dongjak-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 9  Nodeul Station  Exit 1,  432m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68827&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68828&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68830&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68829&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73780&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.513839,'ENP004513'),
(110,'Kyungguksa','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-kgtemple/ENPkxi16h','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}Gyeongguksa Temple, nestled on the eastern slopes of Samgaksan (now known as Bukhansan), is a historic temple founded in the late Goryeo period. Renowned for its scenic mountain surroundings and fresh spring water, it attracts many visitors. The temple complex has 17 buildings, including Geungnakbojeon (Hall of Supreme Bliss), Yeongsanjeon, Myeongbujeon, Gwaneumjeon, and Sibangseonwon. Geungnakbojeon houses the Amitabha Buddha triad, along with wooden Buddhist paintings (designated as Treasure No. 748), Shinjungtaenghwa, and Palsangtaenghwa. Sibangseonwon offers a weekly Sunday meditation session, and the temple also hosts temple stay programs at Hwanheodang and Manwoldang. As one of Seoul\'s significant temples, Gyeongguksa was frequently visited by former President Syngman Rhee. During his tenure as Vice President, Richard Nixon of the United States visited the temple and later described it as one of his most memorable experiences in his memoirs, even including a photograph of his visit.','-3662','','','02705  113-10 Bogungmun-ro, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway  Ui-Sinseol Line  Bukhansan Bogungmun Station  Exit 2, 