(225,'Children\'s Folk Museum','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Childrens-Folk-Museum/ENP005130','Located at the National Folk Museum of Korea, the Children??s Folk Museum offers fun hands-on experiences relating to traditional Korean culture. The Children\'s Folk Museum charges no admission and it is located next to the second exhibition hall of the National Folk Museum of Korea. Capacity is limited and operating hours differ by month, so please check in hours advance. 50 people are admitted at a time, for thirty minutes sessions.','-8164','09:30 - 17:00','Closed Mondays, January 1st, Lunar New Year & Chuseok','03045,  37, Samcheong-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3 Anguk Station Exit 1, 900m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16495&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16496&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16497&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72912&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=72913&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.578051,'ENP005130'),
(226,'Figure Museum W','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Figure-Museum-W/ENP015863','The Figure Museum W is a museum dedicated to figurines and toys! Visitors to Seoul who have an interest in figurines, anime, and toys should make time to visit the museum. Exhibitions at the museum feature beloved superhero and animated figurines. Visitors can also purchase figures and souvenirs at the museum\'s gift shop.','-9297','Weekdays 13:00~17:00 Weekends 11:00~18:00','Closed Mondays, New Year\'s Day, Lunar New Year & Chuseok\n(If a holiday falls on a Monday, the museum opens on Monday and closes the following day.)','06014  3, Seolleung-ro 158-gil, Gangnam-gu, Seoul','Subway Bundang Line  Apgujeong Rodeo Station  Exit 4,  103m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=8602&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=8603&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=8592&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=8594&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=8596&fileTy=MEDIA&fil',7.000000,37.525801,'ENP015863'),
(227,'Korea University Main Hall & Old Main Library','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Korea-University-Main-Hall--Old-Main-Library/ENP002962','Korea University is one of best universities in all of Korea. Visitors to Seoul can visit the Korea University Main Hall located in Anam-dong, Seoul. This beautiful three-story tall building was built in 1932 during the Japanese colonial period. In 1981 the hall was designated Historic Site No. 285 in 1981. The Old Korea University Main Library, located nearby, was designated Historic Site No. 286 in 1981.','-4324','Same hours as Korea University.','','02841  145, Anam-ro, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 6  Anam Station  Exit 2,  527m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68431&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68432&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68433&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.588750,'ENP002962'),
(228,'Shuim Museum','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Shuim-Museum/ENP029578','Shuim Museum aims to preserve a forgotten culture by integrating it with contemporary culture and arts. Highlighting a heavy theme of life and death, the museum remodeled the founder\'s house as an exhibition venue and resting area. Holding exhibition on the museum\'s collection and various contemporary artists, Shuim Museum hopes to facilitate and encourage communications about art with its visitors.','-9593','* Summer (Apr - Oct)\n- Tue - Sat 10:00 - 18:00 (KST)\n- Sun 14:00 - 19:00 (KST)\n\n* Winter (Nov - Mar)\n- Tue - Sat 10:00 - 17:00 (KST)\n- Sun 14:00 - 18:00 (KST)','','03015  209-17, Segeomjeong-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 3,  0212, 1020, 1711, 7016, 7018, 7022 (Get off at Sangmyung University Entrance). Subway Line 5  Gwanghwamun Station  Exit 3,  in front of Kyobo Building, 0212, 1020, 1711, 7016, 7018 (Get off at Sangmyung Unive','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22454&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22455&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22456&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22457&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.599483,'ENP029578'),
(229,'National Palace Museum of Korea','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/National-Palace-Museum-of-Korea/ENP020550','The National Palace Museum of Korea showcases 500 years of history with roughly 45,000 artifacts from the Joseon Dynasty. Artifacts on display include texts and poems that were handwritten by kings of the past, robes worn by royalty, jewelry, and other items from the royal courts of Korea. Highlights from the museum collection are many, one highlight is the royal vehicle of Emperor Sunjong, the last king of the Joseon Dynasty. Another highlight of the colelction is the rain gauge pedestal. The rain gauge pedestal was an invention that dated back to the Joseon era.The museum also offers a learning program called \"Experiencing Royal Culture;\" the program is suitable for people of all ages. Spend time at the National Palace Museum of Korea to experience and learn about the grandeur and history of Korea\'s royalty.??Joseon Dynasty: The royal dynasty lasted from 1392 until 1910. The 518-year reign of the royal Lee family spanned 27 generations.??Rain Gauge Pedestal: The device was used to measure rainfall.??Royal Vehicle of Emperor Sunjong: The vehicle is a 1918 model of the General Motors Cadillac Limo usine.','-11121','Daily 10:00 - 18:00 \n* Wednesday · Saturday 10:00 - 21:00','Open year round','03045  12, Hyoja-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 5,  135m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=14392&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=14393&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=14394&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=14395&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.577021,'ENP020550'),
(230,'Chung Won San Bang','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Cheongwon-Sanbang/ENP004996','The name \"Cheongwon Sanbang\" is derived from Shim Yong-sik\'s carpenter\'s pen name \"Cheongwon\" and means \"clear and round.\" Still making all the doors by hand in a traditional way, the center is dedicated to researching and preserving the window-knitting art, the face of hanok architecture. Shim Yong-sik, a craftsman who reinterprets traditional windows in a modern way and makes original windows, was selected as Seoul\'s Intangible Cultural Property No. 26 in 2006 in recognition of his achievements.','-3977','Saturday 10:00~17:00 (by appointment)','By reservation','03056  27, Bukchon-ro 6-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 3,  430m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60830&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60831&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60833&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=60832&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.580427,'ENP004996'),
(231,'Cheongwadae Sarangchae','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Cheongwadae-Sarangchae/ENP006007','Cheongwadae Sarangchae is a historical memorial museum where visitors can learn about the past, present, and future visions of Seoul and Korea. Originally the home of the public information hall of Cheongwadae (the Blue House, the Korean presidential residence) called ??Hyojadong Sarangbang?? it re-opened with its present name in January 2010 after extensive renovation. Cheongwadae Sarangchae is a two-story building, with exhibition halls, souvenir shops, a resting area on the first floor, and experience zones on the second floor.Cheongwadae Sarangchae features the Korea Hall, the Hi Seoul Hall, a traditional handicrafts demonstration room, a souvenir shop, and a café on the first floor. Various cultural events, such as demonstrations of traditional handicrafts and traditional Korean tea tasting, are held regularly in the lobby. The souvenir shop stocks Cheongwadae-themed goods and traditional Korean items. After viewing the exhibitions, it is pleasant to take a break at the café and enjoy a cup of traditional Korean tea.The Presidential Hall on the second floor displays material about the former presidents of Korea. Here visitors can explore the political and economic events of Korea from the past up to the present day via pictures and visuals. Visitors can also see at a glance a chronology of the past 60 years of Korean history, as well as the major events in the democratization and industrialization of Korea.','-241','','- Closed Tuesdays (If a national holiday falls on Tuesdays, closed on the following weekdays)\n- On January 1st','45, Hyoja-ro 13-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  Exit 4,  800m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=21561&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=21562&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=21563&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.582626,'ENP006007'),
(232,'Korea Furniture Museum','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Korea-Furniture-Museum/ENP003452','The Korea Furniture Museum is a unique museum that focuses only on traditional wooden furniture. The museum\'s collection boasts more than 2,500 pieces of traditional Korean furniture. Rather than exhibiting the collection behind glass in a regular museum set-up, the pieces are displayed in 10 hanok to show visitors how these pieces would have actually been used in daily life. Visitors must make reservations in advance to visit the museum. Reservations can be made online in English at the museum\'s website and the ticket includes a guided tour.','-846','*The museum is currently closed for renovation.','Closed Mondays, Sundays & Public Holidays','02822  121, Daesagwan-ro, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4, Hansung University Station Exit 6, take Bus No. 02 to Seongbuk and get off at the entrance of the Korea Furniture Museum, 196m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16430&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16431&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16432&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L',3.000000,37.599143,'ENP003452'),
(233,'Bukchon Asian Cultural Art Museum','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Bukchon-Asian-Cultural-Art-Museum/ENP005667','The Bukchon Asian Cultural Art Museum displays Korean and Asian artwork. The museum\'s founder, Kwon Youngdu, dedicated 30 years of his life to collecting art from Korea and other parts of Asia. Located in the Bukchon Hanok Village, the museum was constructed in the style of a traditional Korean hanok. The museum also offers activities programs such as folk painting and traditional cooking.','-833','10:00 - 18:30','','03052  76, Bukchon-ro 11-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 2,  903m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=3183&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=3184&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=3185&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73779&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.584025,'ENP005667'),
(234,'Seoul Metropolitan Library','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seoul-Metropolitan-Library/ENP010231','The former Seoul City Hall has reopened its doors as the city\'s main public library. Seoul Metropolitan Library is the city\'s main public library and it\'s easily accessible from City Hall Station\'s exit 4 or 5. The \"Tong Tong\" Seoul City Walking Tour takes visitors through the library and the new Seoul City Hall building. Tours are free and led by a cultural tour guide.','-2353','* Weekdays 09:00 - 21:00 KST\n* Weekends 09:00 - 18:00 KST','Closed Mondays','04524   110, Sejong-daero, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1 / 2, City Hall Station, Exits 4,  126m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68405&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68406&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=70522&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68407&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68408&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.566585,'ENP010231'),
(235,'Beautiful Tea Museum','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Beautiful-Tea-Museum/ENP004467','The Beautiful Tea Museum collects and exhibits information and items related to tea. Located in an elegant Hanok in the Insa-dong area, visitors can learn about and sample a wide range of teas. There are also porcelain works on display and for purchase from talented ceramists. At the tea shop inside the museum, over 110 kinds of tea from around the world including Korea, China, Japan, and Europe are on offer. Admission to the museum is free.','-7333','Gallery 11:30 - 20:00 KST\n* Museum open year-round','Open year round','03162  19-11, Insadong-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/3/5, Jongno 3(sam)-ga Station  Exit 5,  241m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12515&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12516&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12517&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=12518&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73973&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.572289,'ENP004467'),
(236,'Popcon D Square','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Popcon-D-Square/ENP025768','Popcon D Square is a cultural space operated by Daewon Media, a company specializing in animation. Through spaces that reflect the imaginary more than reality, visitors will be sure to enjoy their experiences here.    A place that shows a wide range of exhibitions not limited to a country or genre, Popcon D Square continues to expand itself as a place where visitors can come to enjoy culture and content within the city.','-9293','Weekdays 10:30 - 20:30\nFridays & Weekends 10:30 - 21:00','','04377  55, Hangang-daero 23-gil, Yongsan-gu, Seoul  Hyundai I-Park Mall, Popcon D Square','Subway Line 4, Sinyongsan Station, Exit 2,  240m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=19474&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=19476&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=19477&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=19478&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=19479&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.528707,'ENP025768'),
(237,'Choonwondang Museum of Korean Medicine','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Choonwondang-Museum-of-Korean-Medicine/ENP002637','The Choonwondang Museum of Korean Medicine first opened in 2008 and is dedicated to hanbang, also known as Oriental medicine. The museum spans 7 floors, from the B1 level to the 6th floor and there are exhibitions halls, a decocting room, a quality inspection facility, a cultural space, a doctor??s office and an infirmary. The museum\'s exhibition halls display various historical artifacts relating to Oriental medicine. Display pieces date from the Three Kingdoms era to the Joseon Dynasty. The museum is gaining popularity as a new cultural venue where people can learn about Korean culture and hanbang.','-5597','Mondays-Fridays 09:00 - 18:00 (KST)\nSaturdays 09:00 - 13:00 (KST)','Closed Sundays & national holidays','03139  27, Donhwamun-ro 9-gil, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 1/3/5, Jongno 3(sam)-ga Station  Exit 5,  186m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16319&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16320&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16321&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16322&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75418&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.571592,'ENP002637'),
(238,'Heunginjimun Gate (Dongdaemun)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Heunginjimun-Gate/ENP001999','Heunginjimun Gate is a major historical site in Seoul. More commonly known as Dongdaemun Gate (Great Eastern Gate), it was designated treasure no. 1 by the Korean government. During the Joseon Dynasty, Heunginjimun Gate was one of eight city gates along the historic Seoul City Wall and it served as the main gate for the eastern part of the city. Heunginjimun is known for its exquisite architecture and beauty; the gate is also a spectacular sight at night. After viewing Heunginjimun, visitors may want to explore the Dongdaemun neighborhood and do some late-night shopping.','-1063','Open 24 hours','','03119,  288, Jong-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul)','Subway Lines 1/4  Dongdaemun Station  Exit 9,  74m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68287&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68288&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68289&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68290&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75277&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.570891,'ENP001999'),
(239,'Hongjimun Gate and Tangchundaeseong Fortress','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Hongjimun-Gate-and-Tangchundaeseong-Fortress/ENP004101','Tangchundaeseong Fortress was built in 1712 during the Joseon Dynasty to improve the defense of Hanyangdoseong, the Seoul City Wall, and the Bukhansanseong Fortress. Hongjimun Gate was built during the reign of King Sukjong, the 19th king of the Joseon Dynasty. Legend has it that King Sukjong wrote ??Hongjimun??on the gate\'s original name-board himself and the gate was called Hongjimun thereafter. After passing through Hongjimun Gate, Tangchundaeseong Fortress comes into view. These days, the Tangchundaeseong area offers one of the most beloved hiking trails in Seoul. The hiking trail has a gentle slope for leisurely walks.','-40','Open 24 hours','','03021  212 Segeomjeong-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','subway line 3  Hongje Station  exit 1,   take the bus toward Sangmyung University, and get off in front of Sangmyung University.','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16353&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16354&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16355&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=16356&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75427&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.599012,'ENP004101'),
(240,'Changuimun Gate','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Changuimun-Gate/ENP003266','Located in Buam-dong, Changuimun Gate is one of the four minor city gates of Seoul. It is also sometimes referred to as Bukmun (North Gate) or Jahamun. The gate was built by King Taejo, the first king of the Joseon Dynasty, when he constructed the fortifications surrounding the capital. In Korean history, Changuimun Gate is best known by Koreans as the gate that the rebellion faction used to enter Seoul in the Coup of 1623. A road was built to the west of the gate that accommodates traffic but Changuimun Gate itself is closed.','-10574','','','03020  118, Changuimun-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','subway line 3  Gyeongbokgung Station  exit 3,  take local bus 1020 or 7022, get off at Jahamun Pass/Yun Dong-ju Literature Museum, 51m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22976&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22977&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22978&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22979&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.596615,'ENP003266'),
(241,'Gyeongbokgung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Gyeongbokgung/ENP000072','Gyeongbokgung Palace was the first and largest of the royal palaces built during the Joseon Dynasty. Built in 1395, Gyeongbokgung Palace was located at the heart of the newly appointed capital of Seoul (then known as Hanyang) and represented the sovereignty of the Joseon Dynasty. The largest of the Five Grand Palaces (the others being Gyeonghuigung Palace, Deoksugung Palace, Changgyeonggung Palace, Changdeokgung Palace), Gyeongbokgung served as the main palace of the Joseon Dynasty.                      The Korean government has invested much time and effort into rebuilding, restoring, and maintaining the palace for future generations. These efforts include work to rebuild and restore the buildings that were destroyed during the Japanese occupation. Visitors to Gyeongbokgung can also visit the National Palace Museum of Korea and the National Folk Museum of Korea as they are located on the palace grounds.                    To increase ease of accessibility from Gyeongbokgung Palace to Seochon and vice versa, the palace\'s western gate, Yeongchumun, was opened to the public on December 2018. For the past 43 years, there were only 3 entrances to Gyeongbokgung Palace - the southern gate Gwanghwamun, the northern gate Sinmumun, and the eastern entrance of National folk Museum of Korea. However, with the opening of the western gate Yeongchumun, entry to the palace from all directions has been now made possible.     Frequently Asked Questions about Gyeongbokgung Palace       When is Gyeongbokgung Palace closed?         Gyeongbokgung Palace is closed every Tuesday.If a public holiday and a closed day overlap, the doors will be opened. As a result, the first non-holiday following the open holiday will be the closed day. (As of 2025)         Can I visit Gyeongbokgung Palace for free if I wear a hanbok?         Yes, you can. You can enter Gyeongbokgung Palace for free if you wear a complete hanbok.Please refer to the guidelines regarding detailed hanbok regulations. (As of 2025)         How can I participate in the Gyeongbokgung Palace guided tour?         Groups of less than ten individuals can participate in the guided tour without reservation. Groups of 10 or more people need to make a reservation, and up to 30 people can participate in the tour. You can participate in the regular guided tour of Gyeongbokgung Palace without any reservations. During the tour, you\'ll hear the storyteller\'s narration as you explore the main pavilions of the palace. English tours are available daily at 11:00, 13:30, and 15:30 (except on Tuesdays.) (As of 2025)  Go to Gyeongbokgung Palace Management Office Guided Tour       { \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\", \"@graph\": [{ \"@type\": \"FAQPage\", \"mainEntity\": [{ \"@type\": \"Question\", \"name\": \"When is Gyeongbokgung Palace closed?\", \"acceptedAnswer\": { \"@type\": \"Answer\", \"text\": \"<div>Gyeongbokgung Palace is closed every Tuesday. If a public holiday and a closed day overlap, the doors will be opened. As a result, the first non-holiday following the open holiday will be the closed day. (As of 2024)</div>\" } }, { \"@type\": \"Question\", \"name\": \"Can I visit Gyeongbokgung Palace for free if I wear a hanbok?\", \"acceptedAnswer\": { \"@type\": \"Answer\", \"text\": \"<div>Yes, you can. You can enter Gyeongbokgung Palace for free if you wear a complete hanbok. Please refer to the guidelines regarding detailed hanbok regulations. (As of 2024) <br><br>   <a href=\\\"https://www.royalpalace.go.kr/content/guide/guide01_tab07.asp\\\">Go to the hanbok guidelines.</a> </div>\" } }, { \"@type\": \"Question\", \"name\": \"How can I participate in the Gyeongbokgung Palace guided tour?\", \"acceptedAnswer\": { \"@type\": \"Answer\", \"text\": \"<div> Groups of less than ten individuals can participate in the guided tour without reservation. Groups of less than ten individuals can participate in the guided tour without reservation. Groups of 10 or more people need to make a reservation, and up to 30 people can participate in the tour. You can participate in the regular guided tour of Gyeongbokgung Palace without any reservations. During the tour, you\'ll hear the storyteller\'s narration as you explore the main pavilions of the palace. English tours are available daily at 11:00, 13:30, and 15:30 (except on Tuesdays.) (As of 2024) </div>\" } }] }, { \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\", \"name\": \"Gyeongbokgung\", \"aggregateRating\": { \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\", \"ratingValue\": \"4.5\", \"ratingCount\": \"10892\" }, \"review\": { \"@type\": \"Review\", \"reviewRating\": { \"@type\": \"Rating\", \"ratingValue\": \"5\" }, \"author\": { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"Leila M\" }, \"reviewBody\": \"Gyeongbokgung is a must-visit when in Seoul. This historic palace offers a fascinating glimpse into Korea\'s royal past, with its beautiful architecture, serene gardens, and rich history. The changing of the guard ceremony adds a unique cultural experience, and the palace grounds are perfect for a leisurely stroll. It\'s a place where history and beauty converge, making it a highlight of any trip to Seoul.\", \"datePublished\": \"2024-08-26\" } }] }','-7520','January & February: 09:00 - 17:00\nMarch - May: 09:00 - 18:00\nJune - August: 09:00 - 18:30 \nSeptember & October: 09:00 - 18:00\nNovember & December: 09:00 - 17:00\n*Last entry one hour before closing*','','03045  161, Sajik-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 5, Gwanghwamun Station, Exit 2,  471m\nSubway Line 3, Gyeongbokgung Station, Exit 5,  216m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65749&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65750&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=5&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=65751&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67732&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67733&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.580847,'ENP000072'),
(242,'Sungnyemun Gate (Namdaemun)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Sungnyemun-Gate-Namdaemun-Gate/ENP022888','Sungnyemun Gate (Namdaemun) is one of Seoul\'s historic Four Great Gates and it was designated National Treasure no. 1 by the Korean government in 1962. Though its official name is Sungnyemun, it is also popularly known as Namdaemun Gate due to its location at what was once the southern end of Seoul. As the centuries passed, Seoul grew in size but Sungnyemun Gate has endured through the ages.         Construction on the gate was started in 1395 and completed in 1398. In 1447, Sungnyemun saw reconstruction work carried out. The gate is the largest city gate with an arched entrance in the city, and atop the gate\'s wooden base stands a 2-story wooden structure. The gate is Seoul\'s oldest wooden structure but on Feb. 10th, 2008, much of the gate\'s wooden structure was destroyed by fire. Following several years of restorative work, Sungnyemun Gate can now be enjoyed in all its glory.   ??,-9246,Tue-Sun 09:00-18:00,Monday,04528  40',' Sejong-daero',' Jung-gu',' Seoul\"','Subway Lines 1 / 4 / Gyeongui-Jungang Line/ Airport Railroad  Exit 4,  258m  \nSubway Line 4  Hoehyeon Station  Exit 5,  403m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68265&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68266&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getIm','5',37.558876,126.975904,'ENP022888'),
(243,'Gyeongbokgung Stonewall Walkway','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-gbgstonewall/ENPldz98j','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}The Gyeongbokgung Stonewall Walkway is a walkway that surrounds Gyeongbokgung Palace. Centered around Gwanghwamun, to the left is the west gate of Gyeongbokgung, Yeongchumun; to the north is the north gate, Sinmumun; and to the right is the east gate, Geonchunmun. The left side of the Gyeongbokgung Stonewall Walkway connects to Seochon, while the north connects to the Blue House. The right side leads to Bukchon and Samcheong-dong, where visitors can also explore the National Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art and the National Folk Museum of Korea. The path is well-maintained, perfect for a stroll while experiencing the changing seasons. Walking along the Gyeongbokgung Stonewall Walkway offers a unique view that changes with the weather, whether it\'s raining or snowing.','','','','03045  161 Sajik-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3, Gyeongbokgung Station, Exit 4, 430m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67939&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67940&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67941&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67942&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=73580&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.580847,'ENPldz98j'),
(244,'Changdeokgung Secret Garden','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/2024-cdggarden/ENPl8f5md','.se-contents .se-scrollbox{overflow-x: auto; -ms-overflow-style: none; scrollbar-width: none;}.se-contents .se-scrollbox::-webkit-scrollbar{display: none;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image .se-caption{max-width: 100% !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video{max-width: 100%; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-image > img, .se-contents .se-responsive.se-video > *{max-width: 100%; min-width: 10px; height: auto !important;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper{position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; display: block;}.se-contents .se-responsive.se-video .se-video-wrapper > iframe{width: 100% !important; height: 100% !important; position: absolute; left: 0px}The Secret Garden (Huwon) at Changdeokgung Palace, once used for royal entertainment and ceremonies, is a significant heritage site showcasing traditional landscaping. Covering around 446,943 square meters, this expansive royal garden still has restricted areas that remain inaccessible to the public. Historically, it was off-limits to commoners, reserved only for the Joseon royal family. Nestled against Maebong Peak of Bugaksan Mountain, the garden features several ponds, including Buyongji, home to Buyongjeong Pavilion, Aeryeonji, Jangbangji, and Banwolji. The arrangement of pavilions and buildings reflects traditional Korean architecture, demonstrating a masterful harmony between structures and nature.','-5888','Korean\n- November to February: 10:00 ??15:00 (entry every hour)\n- March to October: 10:00 ??16:00 (entry every hour)\n\nEnglish\n- December to February: 10:30 / 11:30 / 14:3\n- March to November: 10:30 / 11:30 / 14:30 / 15:30\n\nJapanese\n- January to December: ','Closed Mondays. (If the regular closure day falls on a public holiday or substitute holiday, the site will remain open, and the next non-holiday will be the regular closure day.)','03072  99 Yulgok-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 3,  389m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67916&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67917&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67918&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67919&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67920&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.581116,'ENPl8f5md'),
(245,'Gyeonghuigung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Gyeonghuigung/ENP001159','One of the five grand palaces, Gyeonghuigung Palace was also called \"Seogweol\" (which means \"palace of the west\") because it\'s located west of the main palace, Gyeongbokgung. In its heyday, it was part of a vast complex, with 100 buildings in total, but most of these were destroyed during the Japanese occupation. Following intensive restoration work, it reopened to the public in 2002. On its grounds stand the Seoul Museum of History and the Gyeonghuigung Annex Building of the Seoul Museum of Art.    The palace was originally constructed by order of King Gwanghae, the fifteenth king of the Joseon Dynasty, and was completed in 1623. From the beginning, it was much-loved and served as a secondary palace for some ten kings of the Joseon Dynasty.     A variety of Korean art can also be seen in the Gyeonghuigung Annex building of the Seoul Museum of Art, which is situated on the Gyeonghuigung site. Also, the Seoul Museum of History, one of the foremost tourist attractions in the city, houses a permanent collection allowing visitors to see how Seoul has developed and transformed from prehistoric times to the present day.','-918','Daily 09:00 - 18:00 KST *Closed Mondays*','January 1st','03177  45, Saemunan-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 5  Gwanghwamun Station  Exit 1,  875m \nSubway Line 5  Seodaemun Station  Exit 4,  639m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68254&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68255&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68256&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68257&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68258&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.571466,'ENP001159'),
(246,'7th Royal Culture Festival','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/7thRoyalCultureFestival/ENP036912','This year\'s 7th Royal Culture Festival is slated to take place from May 1 (Saturday) to May 9 (Sunday) both on and offline! The festival will take place with several infamous sights set as the background, including Gyeongbokgung Palace, Changdeokgung Palace, Deoksugung Palace, Changgyeonggung Palace, Gyeonghuigung Palace, Jongmyo Shrine, and the Sajikdan Altar. Several culture and arts programming is in store, ranging from on and offline performances utilizing the aesthetic and historical significance of these sites, as well as exhibitions, experiential programs, ceremonial rituals, and more!Festival programming includes the following:An opening ceremony, palaces loved by artists, online children\'s royal culture festival, palace photo contest, royal guard exchange ceremony, saenggwabang, and other programs inclusive of the palace areas.','-7814','','','03045  161, Sajik-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','* Subway Line 3, Gyeongbokgung Station* Subway Line 5, Gwanghwamun Station','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=39987&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=39988&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=39989&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=39990&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=39991&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.580847,'ENP036912'),
(247,'Deoksugung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Deoksugung-Palace/ENP002046','Deoksugung Palace is unique among Korean palaces in having a modern seal engraving and a western style garden and fountain. Medieval and modern style architecture exists together in harmony in Deoksugung Palace. The Changing of the Royal Guard can be seen in front of Daehanmun (Gate) and is a very popular event for many visitors. During the Joseon Dynasty, the royal guard was responsible for opening and closing the palace gate as well as patrolling around the gate area. Outside the palace is a picturesque road flanked by a stone wall which is much loved by visitors.   Originally, Deoksugung Palace was not a palace. The Imjin War (the Japanese invasions in 1592) left all the palaces in Korea severely damaged. When King Seonjo (the fourteenth king of the Joseon Dynasty) returned to Seoul from his evacuation, the primary palace Gyeongbokgung Palace had been burnt to the ground and other palaces were also heavily damaged. A temporary palace was chosen from among the houses of the royal family. This is the origin of Deoksugung Palace. King Gwanghaegun (the fifteenth king of the Joseon Dynasty) named the palace Gyeongungung, formalizing it as a royal palace. Since then it has been used as an auxiliary palace by many Joseon kings. In 1897, Emperor Gojong (the twenty-sixth king of the Joseon Dynasty) stayed here and expanded it. The modern buildings such as Seokjojeon (Hall) were constructed during this period. In 1907, the palace was renamed Deoksugung.','-10642','Daily 9:00 - 21:00 (Last entry 20:00)','Closed Mondays','100-120  99 Sejong-daero, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 1/2 City Hall Station  Exit 1,  72m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67606&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67607&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67608&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67609&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=67610&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.565936,'ENP002046'),
(248,'Unhyeongung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/UnhyeongungPalace/ENP000471','Unhyeongung Palace is one of Seoul\'s smaller palaces and it is an important historic site that is open to the public. The palace was formerly the private residence of Emperor Gojong\'s father, the prince regent Heungseon Daewongun. The young Gojong lived here before he assumed the throne and his wedding to Myeongseong took place here. An annual re-enactment of the royal wedding ceremony between Emperor Gojong and Empress Myeongseong takes place here at the palace.      During the reign of Emperor Gojong, Unhyeongung was as grand as any other palace in Seoul, but over time, many of the palace buildings were heavily damaged and destroyed. Today, visitors can see what has been preserved of the palace and take part in traditional cultural activities and crafts experiences. On weekends, visitors can watch Seoulites get married in traditional Korean wedding ceremonies at the palace.','-9776','Daily 09:00 - 19:00 KST (Last entry 18:30 KST ) *Closed Mondays*','Closed Mondays \n* Open on Mondays falling on public holidays','03131  464, Samil-daero, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 4,  103m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68420&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68421&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68423&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68424&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=3&thumbTy=L',4.000000,37.576397,'ENP000471'),
(249,'Changgyeonggung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Changgyeonggung-Palace/ENP000297','Changgyeonggung Palace was built in 1483 by King Seongjong (the ninth king of the Joseon Dynasty) to take care of the wives of the preceding kings. Compared to other palaces, the size of the palace is compact and simple. Changgyeonggung Palaceis connected with Changdeokgung Palace. It\'s located east of the primary palace of Gyeongbokgung, so it is also referred to as \"Donggwol,\" the \"East Palace.\"Myeongjeongjeon is the main hall of the palace, where state affairs were held, such as meetings with officials and the reception of foreign envoys. In particular, Myeongjeongjeon represents an outstanding example of seventeenth century Joseon architectural style and is the oldest main hall of any palace. While visiting Changgyeonggung Palace, it is recommended you visit nearby Changdeokgung Palace as well.Most of the palace buildings were destroyed by the Japanese during the Japanese invasion of Korea in 1592. The main buildings such as Myeongjeongjeon, Munjeongjeon (council hall), Hwangyeongjeon (Hall), Inyangjeon (Hall), Gongsacheong, and Honghwamun (Gate) were rebuilt by King Gwanghaegun (the fifteenth king of the Joseon Dynasty). During the Japanese occupation, the Japanese built a zoo on the site and renamed the palace \"Changgyeongwon,\" meaning \"Changgyeong Garden.\" Since 1987, the palace has been reconstructed and now resembles its original form. { \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\", \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\", \"name\": \"Changgyeonggung Palace\", \"aggregateRating\": { \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\", \"ratingValue\": \"4.5\", \"ratingCount\": \"765\" }, \"review\": [{ \"@type\": \"Review\", \"reviewRating\": { \"@type\": \"Rating\", \"ratingValue\": \"5\" }, \"author\": { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"MyNeoAj\" }, \"reviewBody\": \"I would recommend you to renting a hanbok before come here,It\'s a good experience you should do. Take a picture with the palace and Royal guard. Don\'t miss to see the Palace Royal Guard Changing Ceremony too.\", \"datePublished\": \"2022-11-25\" }] }','-5550','Daily 09:00 - 21:00 (Last entry at 20:00)','Closed Mondays','03072  185, Changgyeonggung-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Hyehwa Station  Exit 4,  779m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68030&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68031&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68032&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68033&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68034&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.581116,'ENP000297'),
(250,'Hyehwamun Gate','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Hyehwamun-Gate/ENP023606','Hyehwamun Gate is one of Seoul\'s 4 minor city gates. It was built in 1397 along the famed Hanyangdoseong, Seoul City Wall along the Joseon-era eastern boundary of the city. Hyehwamun Gate was also known as Dongsomun Gate (Minor East Gate). Today, it is easily accessible on foot and it is a picturesque and historic Seoul attraction.','-40','','','03076  307, Changgyeonggung-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 4  Hansung University Station  Exit 5,  192m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22964&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22965&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22966&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22967&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22968&fileTy=MEDI',6.000000,37.587767,'ENP023606'),
(251,'Hanyangdoseong (Seoul City Wall)','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Seoul-City-Wall/ENP000090','The Seoul City Wall was originally built in 1396, surrounding Seoul (then known as  Hanyang) during the Joseon Dynasty (1392-1897). The wall stretches for 18.6km along the ranges of Bugaksan Mountain, Naksan Mountain, Namsan Mountain, and Inwangsan Mountain. The wall stands at average heights of 7 - 8 m high. Along the Seoul City Wall, there once stood eight gates that were originally built between 1396-1398, but only six remain standing. The North, South, East, and West gates of the wall are known as the ??Four Great Gates??(Sukjeongmun, Heunginjimun, Sungnyemun, Dongeuimun), while the Northwest, Northeast, Southwest, and Southwest gates are known as the ??Four Minor Gates??(Changuimun, Hyehwamun, Gwanghuimun, Soeuimun).        {  \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\",  \"@type\": \"FAQPage\",  \"mainEntity\": [{    \"@type\": \"Question\",    \"name\": \"How long is the Seoul City Wall in kilometers?\",    \"acceptedAnswer\": {      \"@type\": \"Answer\",      \"text\": \"<div> The total length of the Seoul City Wall is 18.6 km. There are four main and four small gates, consisting of a total of 6 sections. </div>\"    }  },{    \"@type\": \"Question\",    \"name\": \"Is there a commentary program for the Seoul City Wall?\",    \"acceptedAnswer\": {      \"@type\": \"Answer\",      \"text\": \"<div> Yes, commentary programs are available and you can listen to various stories while walking. Each program has different times, routes, and reservation methods, so please check the website below for details.<br><br> <a href=\\\"https://seoulcitywall.seoul.go.kr/content/131.do\\\"style=\\\"color:#0000EE;text-decoration:underline\\\">Seoul City Wall Commentary Program Information</a> </div>\"    }  },{    \"@type\": \"Question\",    \"name\": \"I am curious about the procedure of getting the Seoul City Wall certificate of completion.\",    \"acceptedAnswer\": {      \"@type\": \"Answer\",      \"text\": \"<div> The procedure for getting the Seoul City Wall completion certificate is as follows. \'Get the map ??put the stamp ??take a certified photo ??apply for issuance ??validate the visit\'. Detailed step-by-step details can be found on the website below.<br><br> <a href=\\\"https://seoulcitywall.seoul.go.kr/content/132.do\\\"style=\\\"color:#0000EE;text-decoration:underline\\\">Guide to Issuing Certificate of Completion</a> </div>\"    }  },{  \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\",  \"name\": \"Seoul City Wall\",  \"aggregateRating\": {    \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\",    \"ratingValue\": \"4.5\",    \"ratingCount\": \"174\"  },  \"review\": {    \"@type\": \"Review\",    \"reviewRating\": {      \"@type\": \"Rating\",      \"ratingValue\": \"5\"    },    \"author\": {      \"@type\": \"Person\",      \"name\": \"Gombung\"    },    \"reviewBody\": \"Nice fortress in the middle of a city!    The fortress itself is just okay.    But the specail thing is that it is inside the city circumsized with bulding forests.    Don\'t forget to visit and have a walk here.\",    \"datePublished\": \"2022-06-26\"  }}]}','-40','','','03038  283, Yulgok-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul (Jongno 6-ga, Seoul Design Support Center)','Subway Lines 1 / 4  Dongdaemun Station  Exit 1,  287m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68354&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68355&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68356&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68357&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=68358&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.571951,'ENP000090'),
(252,'Changdeokgung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Changdeokgung-Palace/ENP000295','Changdeokgung Palace is the second UNESCO World Heritage Site in Seoul. It was selected as a representative palace for its notable beauty in the history of palace architecture in East Asia and for its excellent arrangement with the surrounding naturalenvironment. Changdeokgung Palace was built by King Taejong in 1405.   During the Imjin War, Joseon lost both Gyeongbokgung Palace and Changdeokgung Palace. Reconstructed in the 2nd year of Gwanghaegun (1610), Changdeokgung was used as the royal palace of Joseon for about 270 years.    Changdeokgung Palace has two major tour programs. The first is the general tour, which is a basic tour that covers Injeongjeon (仁政???, the main hall, and Nakseonjae (樂善???. The second is a special tour of Howon, which runs from Buyongji, the entrance toHowon, to Okryucheon. The conservation of the ecosystem is absolutely stunning and includes various ponds and gardens.   { \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\", \"@type\": \"LocalBusiness\", \"name\": \"Changdeokgung Palace\", \"aggregateRating\": { \"@type\": \"AggregateRating\", \"ratingValue\": \"4.5\", \"ratingCount\": \"4692\" }, \"review\": [{ \"@type\": \"Review\", \"reviewRating\": { \"@type\": \"Rating\", \"ratingValue\": \"5\" }, \"author\": { \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"Arielle P\" }, \"reviewBody\": \"I love the secret garden and it makes a really unique trip and special memories. We always love to visit in the fall!! The ginkgo trees are remarkable.\", \"datePublished\": \"2024-08-29\" }] }','-5888','February - May, 09:00 - 18:00 (Last entry at 17:00)\nJune - August, 09:00 - 18:30 (Last entry at 17:30)\nSeptember - October, 09:00 - 18:00 (Last entry at 17:00)\nNovember - January, 09:00 - 17:30 (Last entry at 16:30)','Closed Mondays','03072  2-71, Waryong-dong, Jongno-gu, Seoul','Subway Line 3  Anguk Station  Exit 3,  389m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66705&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=7&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66706&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=6&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66707&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=4&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66708&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=5&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=66709&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.581116,'ENP000295'),
(253,'Chundangji Pond','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Chundangji-Pond/ENP039629','On the rear garden grounds of Changgyeonggung Palace sits Chundangji Pond. It is known for its beautiful nature and fall foliage. Chundangji consists of two parts. The smaller upper half is the original location of the pond, while the lower half was initially used as a naenongpo , a place for the royal court to experiment with planting crops such as rice. However, during the Japanese occupation in 1909, the naenongpo was converted into a pond. In 1986, it was renovated into a traditional Korean style. Visitors can also see the seven-story pagoda, made in 1470, sitting on the shore of the pond.','-5550','Daily 09:00 - 21:00 (Last entry at 20:00)','Every Monday (if the closed day falls on a public holiday, it will be closed the following day)','03072  185, Changgyeonggung-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul, Korea (??룡동, 창경???','Subway Line 4  Hyehwa Station  Exit 4,  994m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=48411&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=48412&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=48413&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75415&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=75416&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.578815,'ENP039629'),
(254,'Gwanghuimun Gate','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Gwanghuimun-Gate/ENP023605','Gwanghuimun Gate is one of the Seoul\'s 4 minor city gates. It is located along the southeastern boundary of Joseon-era Seoul. It was known by two other names throughout history, Sugumun Gate and Sigumun Gate. In 1719, it was officially named Gwanghuimun Gate and its name has been the same ever since. In 1975, the gate underwent successful restoration work. Visitors can stop by and see the gate as it is located near the modern Seoul landmark, Dongdaemun History and Culture Park.','-9171','','','04612  350 Toegye-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul','Subway Lines 2/4/5  Dongdaemun History and Culture Park Station   Exit 3,  143m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22959&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22960&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22961&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22962&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=22963&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.564037,'ENP023605'),
(255,'Grand Greenhouse Changgyeonggung Palace','https://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/GrandGreenhouseChanggyeonggungPalace/ENP037176','Changgyeonggung Palace, one of the four main historical palaces in Seoul, houses a greenhouse built in 1909. It is Korea\'s first greenhouse designed in a Western architectural style. Initially, there was a botanical garden and a zoo. In 2004, the building was restored, retaining the original appearance of the greenhouse, and is open to the public. Here you will find different types of plants, both local and imported from other countries.','-10197','09:00 - 20:45','Mondays','03072  185, Changgyeonggung-ro, Jongno-gu, Seoul, Korea (창경???','Subway Line 4  Hyehwa Station  Exit 4,  779m','https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=40391&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=40393&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=40555&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=2&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74820&fileTy=MEDIA&fileNo=1&thumbTy=L | https://english.visitseoul.net/comm/getImage?srvcId=MEDIA&parentSn=74821&fileTy=MEDI',5.000000,37.578815,'ENP037176');
INSERT INTO `conversations` VALUES
(1,1,NULL,'안녕','안녕하세요! 😊 여행 계획에 대해 이야기해보고 싶으신가요? 어디로 가고 싶으신지 궁금합니다!','2025-10-21 02:29:24'),
(2,1,NULL,'제주도 추가해줘','제주도는 정말 아름다운 여행지죠! 🌊 여기서 즐길 수 있는 몇 가지 추천 명소와 활동을 소개해 드릴게요.\n\n1. **한라산**: 제주도의 상징적인 산으로, 하이킹을 즐기면서 경치를 감상할 수 있습니다. 정상에서의 풍경은 정말 환상적이에요!\n\n2. **제주 해변**: 협재해변, 함덕해변 등 다양한 해변이 있어요. 맑고 푸른 바다에서 수영이나 해수욕을 즐기시면 좋습니다. 🏖️\n\n3. **우도**: 제주도에서 배를 타고 갈 수 있는 작은 섬으로, 자전거를 타고 섬을 둘러보는 것이 인기예요. 특히, 우도의 땅콩 아이스크림이 유명하답니다! 🍦\n\n4. **성산일출봉**: 일출 명소로 유명한 곳으로, 이른 아침에 방문하면 멋진 일출을 감상할 수 있어요. 가벼운 등산도 가능하답니다.\n\n5. **제주 전통 시장**: 동문시장이나 신제주관광단지에서 제주 특산물을 구경하고, 맛있는 음식을 즐길 수 있어요. 🥘\n\n여행 일정을 어떻게 계획하고 싶으신가요? 특별히 가고 싶은 장소나 활동이 있다면 말씀해 주세요! 😊','2025-10-21 02:29:44'),
(3,1,NULL,'hello','안녕하세요! 😊 어떻게 도와드릴까요? 여행 계획이나 여행지 추천이 필요하신가요?','2025-10-21 08:10:31'),
(4,1,NULL,'그래 반가워 추가해줘','안녕하세요! 반갑습니다 😊 여행 계획에 어떤 도움이 필요하신가요? 여행지 추천이나 일정 계획 등 무엇이든 말씀해 주세요!','2025-10-21 08:10:50'),
(5,1,NULL,'hello','안녕하세요! 😊 여행 계획에 대해 이야기해볼까요? 어떤 여행을 계획하고 계신가요?','2025-10-21 08:11:25'),
(6,1,NULL,'한국여행 가고싶어','한국 여행을 계획하고 계시는군요! 정말 좋은 선택이에요. 😊 한국에는 아름다운 자연, 역사적인 유적지, 맛있는 음식이 가득하답니다. 어떤 지역이나 도시를 가고 싶으신지 말씀해 주시면, 그에 맞는 정보를 제공해 드릴게요! 예를 들어 서울, 부산, 제주도 등 어떤 곳을 생각하고 계신가요?','2025-10-21 08:11:40'),
(7,1,NULL,'제주도 가고싶어','제주도는 정말 아름다운 곳이죠! 🌊🌺 제주도는 자연 경관이 뛰어나고, 맛있는 음식과 다양한 문화 체험이 가능해서 많은 분들이 사랑하는 여행지입니다.\n\n어떤 일정이나 활동을 계획하고 계신가요? 혹시 가고 싶은 특정 장소나 활동이 있으신가요? 예를 들어, 한라산 등반, 해변에서의 휴식, 또는 맛집 탐방 등 어떤 것을 원하시는지 알려주시면 더욱 구체적으로 도와드릴 수 있습니다! 😊','2025-10-21 08:11:49'),
(8,1,NULL,'내 여행지에 제주도 추가해줘','제주도는 정말 멋진 여행지죠! 🌊🌺 제주도는 아름다운 자연경관과 독특한 문화, 맛있는 음식이 가득한 곳입니다. \n\n제주도에서 추천할 만한 명소 몇 가지를 소개해드릴게요:\n\n1. **한라산**: 제주도의 중심에 위치한 한라산은 등산이나 하이킹을 즐기기에 좋은 곳입니다. 특히 정상에서의 경치는 환상적이에요!\n\n2. **성산 일출봉**: 일출을 감상하기에 최적의 장소로 유명합니다. 아름다운 풍경과 함께하는 아침은 잊지 못할 경험이 될 거예요.\n\n3. **제주 올레길**: 제주를 따라 조성된 다양한 코스의 도보길로, 바다와 자연을 가까이에서 느낄 수 있습니다.\n\n4. **협재 해수욕장**: 맑고 푸른 바다와 하얀 모래사장이 아름다운 해수욕장으로, 여름철에 특히 인기입니다.\n\n5. **오설록 티 뮤지엄**: 제주에서 재배되는 다양한 차를 경험하고 맛볼 수 있는 곳으로, 차 문화에 대해 배울 수 있습니다.\n\n또한, 제주도에는 맛있는 제주 흑돼지와 신선한 해산물도 많으니 꼭 드셔보세요! 😋\n\n여행 일정이나 다른 질문이 있으시면 언제든지 말씀해 주세요!','2025-10-21 08:12:05'),
(9,1,NULL,'내 여행지 리스트 보여줘','여행지 리스트를 보여드릴 수는 없지만, 어떤 여행지를 고려하고 계신지 알려주시면 그에 맞는 정보를 제공해드릴 수 있습니다! 🌍✨ 혹시 가고 싶은 특정한 장소가 있으신가요?','2025-10-21 08:12:19'),
(10,1,NULL,'hello','안녕하세요! 😊 여행 계획에 대해 도와드릴까요? 어떤 여행을 생각하고 계신가요?','2025-10-21 08:17:37'),
(11,1,NULL,'나 홍대가고싶어 ','홍대는 정말 매력적인 장소죠! 🎉 젊음과 창의력이 넘치는 분위기와 다양한 문화적 경험이 가득한 곳이에요. \n\n홍대에서는 무엇을 하고 싶으신가요? 예를 들어, 쇼핑, 맛집 탐방, 카페 방문, 공연 관람 등 다양한 활동이 가능해요. 어떤 일정으로 계획해 드릴까요? 😊','2025-10-21 08:17:46'),
(12,1,NULL,'여행지 목록 보여줘','물론입니다! 다양한 매력을 가진 여행지를 몇 군데 추천해 드릴게요. 😊\n\n1. **파리, 프랑스** - 에펠탑, 루브르 박물관 등 문화와 예술이 넘치는 도시입니다.\n2. **도쿄, 일본** - 전통과 현대가 공존하는 도시로, 맛있는 음식과 쇼핑이 가득합니다.\n3. **바르셀로나, 스페인** - 가우디의 건축물과 아름다운 해변이 매력적인 도시입니다.\n4. **방콕, 태국** - 화려한 사원과 맛있는 길거리 음식으로 유명한 곳입니다.\n5. **뉴욕, 미국** - 자유의 여신상, 센트럴 파크 등 다양한 명소가 있는 활기찬 도시입니다.\n6. **이탈리아, 로마** - 역사적인 유적지와 맛있는 이탈리안 음식이 매력적인 도시입니다.\n7. **하와이, 미국** - 아름다운 자연 경관과 해변이 있는 휴양지입니다.\n8. **세부, 필리핀** - 아름다운 바다와 리조트가 많은 인기 있는 여행지입니다.\n\n어떤 여행지에 관심이 있으신가요? 더 자세한 정보를 제공해 드릴 수 있습니다! 😊✈️','2025-10-21 08:18:00'),
(13,1,NULL,'아니 내가 추가한 여행지 보여줘','죄송하지만, 제가 사용자가 추가한 여행지를 직접 확인할 수는 없습니다. 하지만 여행지에 대한 정보나 추천을 도와드릴 수 있습니다! 어떤 여행지가 궁금하신가요? 😊','2025-10-21 08:18:17'),
(14,1,NULL,'남한 산성 여행지 추가해줘','남한산성은 정말 멋진 여행지입니다! 🏞️ 이곳은 역사적인 의미와 아름다운 자연 경관을 동시에 즐길 수 있는 곳이죠. \n\n### 남한산성 정보\n- **위치**: 경기도 광주와 성남에 위치하고 있습니다.\n- **역사**: 남한산성은 조선시대의 군사 요새로, 유네스코 세계문화유산으로도 지정되어 있습니다.\n- **주요 볼거리**:\n  - **성곽**: 성벽을 따라 걸으며 경치를 감상할 수 있습니다.\n  - **전망대**: 성곽의 여러 지점에서 멋진 경치를 감상할 수 있습니다.\n  - **사찰**: 망경사와 같은 아름다운 사찰도 있어, 마음의 평화를 찾기 좋은 곳입니다.\n\n### 여행 팁\n- **하이킹**: 남한산성은 하이킹 코스가 잘 마련되어 있어, 걷기 좋은 편입니다. 편안한 신발을 착용하는 것이 좋습니다.\n- **계절별 매력**: 봄에는 벚꽃, 가을에는 단풍이 아름다워 각각의 계절에 따라 다른 매력을 느낄 수 있습니다.\n- **음식**: 주변에 맛있는 전통 음식점들이 많이 있으니, 꼭 한 번 들러보세요!\n\n여행 계획이 필요하시다면, 어떤 일정으로 가고 싶으신지 말씀해 주시면 도와드리겠습니다! 😊','2025-10-21 08:18:42');
